<SYNC Start=4590><P Class=KRCC>
1900년대 초까지 볼츠만은<br>
견디기 힘든 싸움을 계속했습니다
<SYNC Start=9819><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=12554><P Class=KRCC>
그는 우주의 가장 근본적인<br>
작동 원리 중 하나를 밝혀냈고
<SYNC Start=17638><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=17725><P Class=KRCC>
그것에 평생을 바쳤습니다
<SYNC Start=19999><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=20800><P Class=KRCC>
철학자 버트랜드 러셀은<br>
이렇게 말했습니다
<SYNC Start=24419><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=24603><P Class=KRCC>
"만물이 이러한 근본 법칙에 따라<br>
흘러간다는 사실의 발견은.."
<SYNC Start=28702><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=28813><P Class=KRCC>
"..높은 사고력의 소유자라면 누구에게나<br>
압도적인 힘으로 깨달음을 준다."
<SYNC Start=33695><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=35353><P Class=KRCC>
"마치 이탈리아의 언덕을 오르는<br>
등반객의 눈에.."
<SYNC Start=38669><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=38708><P Class=KRCC>
"..가을 안개가 걷히며 드러나는<br>
궁전의 모습처럼."
<SYNC Start=42500><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=45150><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만도 그랬습니다
<SYNC Start=46955><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=47021><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 그에겐 이곳<br>
이탈리아 뒤노가 그 궁전이었습니다
<SYNC Start=51457><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=51535><P Class=KRCC>
그가 목을 매 자살한 곳입니다
<SYNC Start=54197><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=57848><P Class=KRCC>
1906년 볼츠만은 아내와 딸과 함께<br>
휴가차 이곳 뒤노에 왔습니다
<SYNC Start=64184><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=65175><P Class=KRCC>
그의 이론은 여전히 외면받았으며,<br>
그는 지치고 심약해진 상태였죠
<SYNC Start=70057><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=70373><P Class=KRCC>
그는 아내와 딸이 산책 나간 사이에<br>
유서도 남기지 않고 자살했습니다
<SYNC Start=76858><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=96937><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만의 생각을 알 길은 없지만,<br>
짐작은 할 수 있습니다
<SYNC Start=101798><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=102447><P Class=KRCC>
그는 경이로운 발상을 이해하는 것의<br>
무게감을 잘 알고 있었죠
<SYNC Start=107329><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=107443><P Class=KRCC>
이런 말도 했습니다,<br>
"만가(挽歌)를 읊는 시인과도 같이.."
<SYNC Start=112177><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=112323><P Class=KRCC>
"..나는 피를 토하는 심정으로<br>
수학을 연구한다."
<SYNC Start=115943><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=116207><P Class=KRCC>
그가 열정적인 사람이었음을<br>
엿볼 수 있죠
<SYNC Start=118815><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=123931><P Class=KRCC>
또다른 추측도 해 봅니다
<SYNC Start=125792><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=126322><P Class=KRCC>
볼츠만의 주요 논문 중 하나에서
<SYNC Start=129184><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=129347><P Class=KRCC>
그는 괴테의 '파우스트'에 나오는<br>
세 문장을 인용하고 있습니다
<SYNC Start=132642><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=132936><P Class=KRCC>
"진리를 찾아내어라. 그것을 분명하게 기록하라.<br>
목숨을 걸고 그 진리를 지켜라."
<SYNC Start=138143><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=138286><P Class=KRCC>
바로 그 자신이 한 일이죠
<SYNC Start=139935><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=140192><P Class=KRCC>
그런데, 이런 생각이 듭니다
<SYNC Start=142272><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=142448><P Class=KRCC>
과학 논문 첫머리에 왜 하필<br>
파우스트를 인용했을까요?
<SYNC Start=147066><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=148752><P Class=KRCC>
파우스트와 악마가 맺은<br>
계약의 내용은
<SYNC Start=152478><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=152584><P Class=KRCC>
파우스트가 원하는 모든 지식과 경험을<br>
악마가 제공하는 대신
<SYNC Start=157672><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=157724><P Class=KRCC>
파우스트는 어느 한 순간에도<br>
영원히 머무를 수 없다는 것입니다<br>
<font color=magenta>(가장 행복한 순간에 시간을 멈춰달라고 말하면<br>
악마가 파우스트의 영혼을 가져가겠다는 계약)</font>
<SYNC Start=164297><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=164732><P Class=KRCC>
제 생각에는, 볼츠만이<br>
30년간의 힘든 투쟁 뒤에
<SYNC Start=168920><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=169076><P Class=KRCC>
이 아름다운 곳을 찾아와서는
<SYNC Start=172731><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=173228><P Class=KRCC>
이렇게 말하지 않았을까요?
<SYNC Start=175239><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=175425><P Class=KRCC>
"바로 지금 완벽하고 아름다운 순간에<br>
머무르고 싶도다."<br>
<font color=gray>(파우스트가 악마를 불러내는 주문)</font>
<SYNC Start=179851><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=180102><P Class=KRCC>
"여기서 떠나고 싶지 않다.<br>
시간아, 이대로 멈추어다오."<br>
<font color=gray>(파우스트가 악마를 불러내는 주문)</font>
<SYNC Start=186649><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=188965><P Class=KRCC>
논란을 불러 일으킨<br>
볼츠만의 위대한 업적은
<SYNC Start=192478><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=192557><P Class=KRCC>
변하지 않고 완벽한 고전 물리학에
<SYNC Start=197094><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=197174><P Class=KRCC>
흘러가는 시간, 비가역적인 변화라는<br>
개념을 도입한 것입니다
<SYNC Start=201215><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=201469><P Class=KRCC>
그랬던 그 자신이, 삶의 마지막 순간<br>
'시간이 멈추기를' 바랐던 셈이죠
<SYNC Start=207368><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=216971><P Class=KRCC>
아이러니하게도 볼츠만이 죽은 직후<br>
그의 이론이 입증되었습니다
<SYNC Start=221401><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=221591><P Class=KRCC>
조금만 더 기다렸더라면,<br>
볼츠만은
<SYNC Start=225871><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=226092><P Class=KRCC>
20세기 물리학 혁명의 아버지로<br>
일컬어졌을 것입니다
<SYNC Start=232545><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=234236><P Class=KRCC>
시대를 잘못 만난 삶처럼,<br>
죽음도 때이른 것이었습니다
<SYNC Start=238700><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=238905><P Class=KRCC>
그가 물리학에 불확실성이라는<br>
씨앗을 뿌렸지만
<SYNC Start=241961><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=242020><P Class=KRCC>
그것을 가꾼 사람은 없었습니다
<SYNC Start=244433><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=245101><P Class=KRCC>
차라리 그보다는,
<SYNC Start=247533><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=247597><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어가 들춰낸 수학의 불확실성이<br>
주목을 받았습니다
<SYNC Start=252531><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=253256><P Class=KRCC>
새로운 세대의 수학자와 철학자들은
<SYNC Start=257223><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=257392><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어를 좌절시킨<br>
문제와 역설을 해결한다면
<SYNC Start=262163><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=262375><P Class=KRCC>
수학은 다시금 완벽해질 것이라고<br>
자신했습니다
<SYNC Start=265561><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=268961><P Class=KRCC>
그중 가장 유명한 인물인<br>
힐베르트는 이렇게 선언했습니다
<SYNC Start=272778><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=273015><P Class=KRCC>
"인류 지성의 자존심을<br>
지키기 위해서라도.."
<SYNC Start=276548><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=276683><P Class=KRCC>
"..반드시 무한의 본질을<br>
명확하게 밝혀내야만 한다"
<SYNC Start=281608><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=282944><P Class=KRCC>
그들은 확실성을<br>
집요하게 추구한 나머지,
<SYNC Start=286361><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=286488><P Class=KRCC>
논리적이며 증명 가능한 것들만이
<SYNC Start=289034><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=289068><P Class=KRCC>
진정으로 이해할 가치가<br>
있다고 믿었습니다
<SYNC Start=293036><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=293759><P Class=KRCC>
완벽한 논리와 추론 체계를<br>
찾으려는 노력이
<SYNC Start=296750><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=296799><P Class=KRCC>
얼마나 필사적이었는지 보여주는<br>
좋은 예가 여기 있습니다
<SYNC Start=301240><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=301485><P Class=KRCC>
1910년에 씌어진<br>
세 권으로 된 '수학 원리'입니다<br>
<font color=magenta>(by 러셀 & 화이트헤드)</font>
<SYNC Start=305903><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=306321><P Class=KRCC>
이 책은 상당히 많은<br>
분량을 할애하여..
<SYNC Start=310169><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=310406><P Class=KRCC>
1 + 1 = 2 를<br>
증명하고 있습니다
<SYNC Start=313884><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=316106><P Class=KRCC>
또한 그 증명의 상당 부분은<br>
유한과 무한의 문제,
<SYNC Start=321107><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=321129><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 칸토어가 포기했던<br>
역설들을 논하고 있습니다
<SYNC Start=324603><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=327930><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 '수학 원리'의<br>
노력에도 불구하고,
<SYNC Start=329957><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=330020><P Class=KRCC>
논리와 수학에는<br>
이미 금이 가 버렸으며
<SYNC Start=335173><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=335323><P Class=KRCC>
"이게 다 칸토어 때문이다"라는<br>
생각이 팽배해졌습니다
<SYNC Start=338639><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=340315><P Class=KRCC>
오스트리아의 작가 뮤질이<br>
표현했던 바와 같이
<SYNC Start=344043><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=344255><P Class=KRCC>
수학자들은 어느날 갑자기,<br>
이론의 토대가 되는 어떤 주춧돌이
<SYNC Start=348892><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=349017><P Class=KRCC>
절대로 제자리에 놓일 수<br>
없다는 것을 알아챘습니다
<SYNC Start=354127><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=354262><P Class=KRCC>
바닥을 살펴본 뒤, 사실은 모든게<br>
사상누각이었음을 알았습니다
<SYNC Start=361253><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=367689><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어는 수학과 논리의 한계를<br>
끝까지 몰고 간 대가를 치렀습니다
<SYNC Start=373770><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=374174><P Class=KRCC>
삶의 마지막 20년 대부분은<br>
정신병원을 드나들며 보냈습니다
<SYNC Start=379392><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=382440><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어가 할레의 네르펜클리닉에<br>
마지막으로 온 것은 1917년입니다
<SYNC Start=387669><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=387785><P Class=KRCC>
그는 이곳을 끔찍이 싫어했고
<SYNC Start=390467><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=390672><P Class=KRCC>
제발 자기를 꺼내달라고<br>
아내에게 편지를 쓰기도 했습니다
<SYNC Start=393611><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=393769><P Class=KRCC>
이곳엔 그를 포함해<br>
민간인은 두 명 뿐이었고
<SYNC Start=396584><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=396609><P Class=KRCC>
나머지는 1차대전의<br>
사상자들이었습니다
<SYNC Start=400912><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=401697><P Class=KRCC>
1918년 1월 6일
<SYNC Start=404290><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=404393><P Class=KRCC>
이 당대 최고의 수학자는<br>
병실에서 외로이 세상을 떴습니다
<SYNC Start=409530><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=409757><P Class=KRCC>
그의 야심찬 계획을<br>
미완으로 남겨둔 채..
<SYNC Start=412916><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=414429><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어가 빼낸 조약돌은 언젠가<br>
산사태를 일으킬 수도 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=419867><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=420345><P Class=KRCC>
그는, 신은 모든 생각을 통합하고<br>
역설조차 해결할수 있다고 보았습니다
<SYNC Start=427026><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=429078><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 신이 죽어버렸다면<br>
어떻게 해야 합니까..
<SYNC Start=433754><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=434240><P Class=KRCC>
신이 없다면,<br>
산사태는 피할 수 없습니다
<SYNC Start=439714><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=439972><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 1차대전에서 신은 죽었습니다
<SYNC Start=443741><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=446656><P Class=KRCC>
마침내 손에서 미끄러져 나갑니다
<SYNC Start=450103><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=453953><P Class=KRCC>
서양의 역사를 보면, 우리는 줄곧<br>
확실성을 갈구해 오지 않았습니까
<SYNC Start=459526><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=459685><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>루이스 새스 - 임상심리학자, 럿거스 대학</font><br>
설령 옛날에는 그러한 열망이<br>
더 적었다 할지라도, 그 이유는
<SYNC Start=465300><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=465443><P Class=KRCC>
우리 곁엔 이미 확실성, 즉 신이라는<br>
존재가 있다고 가정했기 때문입니다
<SYNC Start=470628><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=470913><P Class=KRCC>
회의주의로 무장한<br>
데카르트<font color=magenta>*</font>마저도<br>
<font color=magenta>* '방법적 회의'에 의한 진리 추구를 주창</font>
<SYNC Start=476378><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=476742><P Class=KRCC>
아무런 문제의식 없이<br>
신의 존재를 당연시했습니다
<SYNC Start=481865><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=482710><P Class=KRCC>
그러니, 이른바 '신의 죽음'<br>
이후에는 대체 어떻게 될 것인가
<SYNC Start=487590><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=487726><P Class=KRCC>
..하는 물음이 제기됩니다
<SYNC Start=490864><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=491085><P Class=KRCC>
신이 죽음에 따라,<br>
인간이 작은 부분을 차지했던
<SYNC Start=497934><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=498090><P Class=KRCC>
초자연적 질서에 대한 믿음도<br>
사그라지게 됩니다
<SYNC Start=503843><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=506404><P Class=KRCC>
1차대전은 모두가 패자였습니다
<SYNC Start=508181><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=508520><P Class=KRCC>
베르사이유 조약<font color=magenta>*</font>은 휴전이었을 뿐<br>
아무것도 해결하지 못했습니다<br>
<font color=magenta>* 1차대전 후 강화조약</font>
<SYNC Start=512917><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=513399><P Class=KRCC>
전쟁 전에 불거진 학문적 위기도<br>
여전히 해결되지 않았습니다
<SYNC Start=518189><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=518577><P Class=KRCC>
'수학 원리' 같은 것도 그저<br>
임시방편에 지나지 않았습니다
<SYNC Start=522895><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=523292><P Class=KRCC>
'수학 원리'는 일면<br>
베르사이유 조약과 비슷합니다
<SYNC Start=525969><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=526003><P Class=KRCC>
분량이 엄청나다는<br>
차이가 있지만요
<SYNC Start=527954><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=528108><P Class=KRCC>
말하자면 시멘트 1만톤을 쏟아부어<br>
수학에 생긴 균열을 메운것입니다
<SYNC Start=533177><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=533683><P Class=KRCC>
얼마간은 그렇게<br>
잘 메워진듯 했습니다
<SYNC Start=536027><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=536953><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 이 비엔나 대학 도서관에<br>
한 젊은이가 찾아옵니다
<SYNC Start=540665><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=540919><P Class=KRCC>
쿠르트 괴델입니다
<SYNC Start=542699><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=543225><P Class=KRCC>
그가 이곳에서 한 연구는
<SYNC Start=545737><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=545810><P Class=KRCC>
완벽한 논리/추론 체계를 향한 꿈을<br>
물거품으로 만들었습니다
<SYNC Start=551563><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=553554><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=yellow>- 논리의 한계 -</font>
<SYNC Start=557735><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=557879><P Class=KRCC>
괴델은 볼츠만이 죽은 해인<br>
1906년 태어났습니다
<SYNC Start=561600><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=561867><P Class=KRCC>
불안정한 시대에 자라난 그는<br>
쉴새없이 질문을 던지는 아이였고
<SYNC Start=566783><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=566988><P Class=KRCC>
가족들은 그를<br>
'미스터 와이(Mr. Why)'라 불렀죠
<SYNC Start=570037><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=570403><P Class=KRCC>
그가 대학에 들어간 때는<br>
1차대전이 끝난 뒤입니다
<SYNC Start=574616><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=574748><P Class=KRCC>
유럽과 마찬가지로<br>
오스트리아는 불황기였으며
<SYNC Start=578557><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=578722><P Class=KRCC>
히틀러는 국가사회주의정당을<br>
만들었습니다
<SYNC Start=581962><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=584107><P Class=KRCC>
그는 뛰어난 젊은 철학자, 정치이론가,<br>
시인, 과학자 등의 모임인
<SYNC Start=590740><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=590796><P Class=KRCC>
'비엔나 서클'에 참여했습니다
<SYNC Start=593714><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=594098><P Class=KRCC>
혼란이 오히려 반가운 때였죠.<br>
사상을 강요하는 중앙 권력이 없으니
<SYNC Start=597190><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=597341><P Class=KRCC>
개개인의 아이디어들이<br>
자랄 수 있죠
<SYNC Start=601478><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=601720><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 혼란은 한편으로는<br>
자유를 가져다주기도 했지만
<SYNC Start=607455><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=607813><P Class=KRCC>
동시에 사람들은 확실한<br>
관념을 찾아 헤매게 되었습니다
<SYNC Start=612649><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=612725><P Class=KRCC>
모든게 허무해 보이니까
<SYNC Start=615107><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=615270><P Class=KRCC>
믿고 따를만한 멋진 생각들을<br>
찾았던 거죠
<SYNC Start=619680><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=619881><P Class=KRCC>
급진주의자, 혁명론자들도<br>
주위에 있었지만
<SYNC Start=623498><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=623535><P Class=KRCC>
괴델 자신은 그 부류에<br>
속하지 않았습니다
<SYNC Start=626028><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=626180><P Class=KRCC>
그는 세상 물정에 무관심하고<br>
꼼꼼한 사람이었으며
<SYNC Start=629684><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=629738><P Class=KRCC>
힐베르트처럼 수학이 언젠가는<br>
완벽함을 되찾을거라 믿었습니다
<SYNC Start=635707><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=636253><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 헛된 꿈이었죠
<SYNC Start=638599><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=639359><P Class=KRCC>
그는 힐베르트 프로그램<font color=magenta>*</font>을<br>
무너뜨릴 생각이 전혀 아니었습니다<br>
<font color=magenta>* 수학의 모든 이론을 엄격하게 형식화하여<br>
무모순의 완전한 체계를 완성하려던 시도</font>
<SYNC Start=646174><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=646258><P Class=KRCC>
산술 체계의 완전성<font color=magenta>*</font>을<br>
증명하는 일이<br>
<font color=magenta>* 어떤 이론 내의 모든 참인 명제가<br>
증명이 가능한가 하는 성질</font>
<SYNC Start=652213><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=652381><P Class=KRCC>
불가능하다는 사실을 깨달았을 때<br>
그 자신도 놀랐을 것입니다
<SYNC Start=659362><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=659641><P Class=KRCC>
순수 수학에서 아주 기괴한<br>
일이 벌어진겁니다
<SYNC Start=662261><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=662432><P Class=KRCC>
블랙홀, 빅뱅, 양자적 불확정성<br>
같은 것만큼이나 요상한..
<SYNC Start=669009><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=669137><P Class=KRCC>
바로 괴델의 불완전성 정리입니다.<br>
당시에는 미스테리였습니다
<SYNC Start=672917><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=673051><P Class=KRCC>
다른건 몰라도 적어도<br>
순수 논리의 세계에서는
<SYNC Start=676195><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=676357><P Class=KRCC>
애매모호함이 없으며<br>
흑백이 분명하다고 여겨져 왔는데
<SYNC Start=679275><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=679450><P Class=KRCC>
그러한 순수 논리에서<br>
불분명한 부분이 드러난겁니다
<SYNC Start=684890><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=696298><P Class=KRCC>
비엔나 서클의 정기 모임이<br>
열렸던 카페입니다
<SYNC Start=700291><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=700621><P Class=KRCC>
1930년 늦여름, 이 카페에서<br>
괴델은 두 동료와 이야기하던 중
<SYNC Start=705864><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=706470><P Class=KRCC>
자신이 연구하던 주제에 대해<br>
잠깐 언급했습니다
<SYNC Start=710636><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=710752><P Class=KRCC>
'불완전성 정리'입니다
<SYNC Start=713201><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=713435><P Class=KRCC>
그가 증명했다고 언급한 내용은
<SYNC Start=717834><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=717933><P Class=KRCC>
모든<font color=magenta>*</font> 수리 논리 체계에는<br>
한계가 있다는 것입니다<br>
<font color=magenta>* 진행자는 줄곧 '모든'이라고 말하고 있는데<br>
사실은 특정조건을 만족하는 체계에 대한 것임</font>
<SYNC Start=722470><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=722804><P Class=KRCC>
참이지만 결코 증명이<br>
불가능한 명제가
<SYNC Start=726589><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=726653><P Class=KRCC>
반드시 존재한다는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=730185><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=730382><P Class=KRCC>
불완전성 정리를 통하여<br>
괴델이 증명한 것은
<SYNC Start=735972><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=736491><P Class=KRCC>
공리들, 즉 논증의 토대를<br>
아무리 크게 확장하더라도
<SYNC Start=743104><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=743272><P Class=KRCC>
산술 체계에는 반드시, 참이지만<br>
증명 불가능한 명제가 있다는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=748612><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=752006><P Class=KRCC>
아무리 많은 데이터를 가져와도
<SYNC Start=756305><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=756475><P Class=KRCC>
참인 명제들 모두를 증명하는 것은<br>
절대로 불가능합니다
<SYNC Start=760806><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=763104><P Class=KRCC>
이로써 르네상스적인 이상,
<SYNC Start=767676><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=767931><P Class=KRCC>
즉 언젠가 수학과 논리로<br>
모든 진리를 증명하게 되어
<SYNC Start=771666><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=771728><P Class=KRCC>
신에 필적할 지식을 획득하리라는<br>
꿈이 무너진 것입니다
<SYNC Start=776129><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=776929><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 이 아이디어는<br>
너무나 뜬구름잡는 것으로 보여서
<SYNC Start=782671><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=782823><P Class=KRCC>
이 동료들 누구도 괴델의 말을<br>
이해하지 못했습니다
<SYNC Start=787053><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=787316><P Class=KRCC>
비유하자면 폭탄이 터졌는데<br>
그 여파를 아직 느끼지 못한거죠
<SYNC Start=793366><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=797254><P Class=KRCC>
이튿날, 이제 수학계의<br>
원로가 된 힐베르트는
<SYNC Start=801160><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=801176><P Class=KRCC>
카페에서 벌어진 일을 모른채<br>
쾨니히스베르크 강연에서
<SYNC Start=806654><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=806760><P Class=KRCC>
이렇게 선언했습니다,<br>
"우리는 알아야만 한다. 우리는 알게 될 것이다."
<SYNC Start=812279><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=813794><P Class=KRCC>
공교롭게도, 그 바로 전날 괴델은
<SYNC Start=817062><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=817148><P Class=KRCC>
'우리가 절대로 알 수 없는'<br>
것들이 있음을 증명했죠
<SYNC Start=822049><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=822886><P Class=KRCC>
이 결과를 언짢아하는<br>
사람들도 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=827734><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=827898><P Class=KRCC>
힐베르트도 처음에는<br>
대단히 화를 냈다고 합니다
<SYNC Start=832192><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=832643><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 이것은<br>
좋다 싫다의 문제가 아닙니다
<SYNC Start=835983><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=836146><P Class=KRCC>
증명이 되었고,<br>
받아들여야만 하는 것이죠
<SYNC Start=840482><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=841185><P Class=KRCC>
괴델의 논증에 허점은 없었을까요?
<SYNC Start=842863><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=843001><P Class=KRCC>
아뇨, 완벽한 증명입니다.<br>
지극히 명료하고 명백한 논리입니다
<SYNC Start=849065><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=850067><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어의 역설을 풀려고 노력한<br>
힐베르트를 도우려다가
<SYNC Start=855639><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=855875><P Class=KRCC>
괴델은 그 노력이 결국<br>
부질없는 것임을 증명했습니다
<SYNC Start=860058><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=860358><P Class=KRCC>
무한에 대한 칸토어의 연구에서<br>
착안한 그의 연구 결과는
<SYNC Start=864643><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=864695><P Class=KRCC>
몇몇 역설들은 해결 불가능하며<br>
더욱 많은 역설들이 있음을 보였습니다
<SYNC Start=870633><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=871905><P Class=KRCC>
하지만 옳은 말을 했다고<br>
꼭 평판까지 얻는 것은 아니죠
<SYNC Start=875713><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=879676><P Class=KRCC>
비엔나 대학 안마당에<br>
다시 왔습니다
<SYNC Start=883041><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=883161><P Class=KRCC>
수많은 석학들의 흉상들이 있죠
<SYNC Start=885747><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=885865><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 괴델은 없습니다
<SYNC Start=890160><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=890845><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 그 이유가 혹시
<SYNC Start=892788><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=892813><P Class=KRCC>
괴델의 연구에 대해 사람들이 가진<br>
불편함 때문은 아니었을까요?
<SYNC Start=897882><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=899625><P Class=KRCC>
제 생각에는, 괴델이 내놓은 결과를<br>
흔쾌히 받아들이는 사람은 없습니다
<SYNC Start=905560><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=905951><P Class=KRCC>
수학자들은 어쨌거나 힐베르트 식으로<br>
형식 체계를 밀고 나가려고 하죠
<SYNC Start=911647><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=912224><P Class=KRCC>
괴델은 그러한 형식주의적<font color=magenta>*</font> 관점을<br>
파괴한 것입니다<br>
<font color=magenta>* 수학을 형식적, 기계적 기호 조작으로 보는 견해.<br>
앞서 말한 힐베르트 프로그램도 여기서 나옴</font>
<SYNC Start=918067><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=918132><P Class=KRCC>
정해진 공리로부터 기계적으로<br>
정리를 찍어내면 된다는 시각을 말이죠<br>
<font color=magenta>(이 말도 형식주의에 대한 설명임)</font>
<SYNC Start=921959><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=921976><P Class=KRCC>
괴델이 그러한 시도를<br>
근본부터 흔들어놓았지만
<SYNC Start=926464><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=926480><P Class=KRCC>
그 현실을 마주하는 것은<br>
불편합니다
<SYNC Start=927988><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=928144><P Class=KRCC>
그러다보니, 괴델에 대한<br>
애증이 교차합니다
<SYNC Start=930160><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=930164><P Class=KRCC>
그가 태어난지 100년이 지난 지금도<br>
매우 이중적인 태도가 있습니다
<SYNC Start=933973><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=934256><P Class=KRCC>
한편으로는 괴델을 역사상<br>
가장 위대한 논리학자로 칭송하지만
<SYNC Start=939142><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=939171><P Class=KRCC>
또 한편으로는,<br>
괴델이 가져온 결과에 대해
<SYNC Start=942204><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=942240><P Class=KRCC>
모르던 사람은 모르고 넘어갔으면<br>
싶어하는 면도 있습니다
<SYNC Start=944275><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=944292><P Class=KRCC>
괴델이 한 말은 결국<br>
논리학에 부족함이 있다는 거니까요
<SYNC Start=947219><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=947353><P Class=KRCC>
외면하고 다른 주제로<br>
넘어가고 싶어하죠
<SYNC Start=950721><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=952739><P Class=KRCC>
괴델 자신도 이 결론이 몰고 온<br>
영향을 실감했습니다
<SYNC Start=956068><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=956467><P Class=KRCC>
이 결과가 함축하는<br>
진정한 의미를 파악해 가면서
<SYNC Start=959945><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=960137><P Class=KRCC>
수학의 본질에 관한<br>
괴델의 믿음도 깎여 나갔습니다
<SYNC Start=965546><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=965871><P Class=KRCC>
건강도 나빠졌고, 자신의<br>
정신 상태까지 걱정되기 시작했죠
<SYNC Start=971205><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=971866><P Class=KRCC>
마침내 1934년<br>
신경쇠약에 걸렸습니다
<SYNC Start=975432><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=976070><P Class=KRCC>
다시 회복되었는가 했으나<br>
문제는 더 커졌습니다
<SYNC Start=980662><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=980825><P Class=KRCC>
그는 중대한 결심을 했습니다
<SYNC Start=983374><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=989736><P Class=KRCC>
불완전성 정리를 내놓은 직후부터
<SYNC Start=992885><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=993016><P Class=KRCC>
그는 중요한 미해결 난제에<br>
착수했습니다
<SYNC Start=996727><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=996878><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어의 연속체 가설이었죠
<SYNC Start=999499><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=999896><P Class=KRCC>
그 영향을 한번 볼까요
<SYNC Start=1001997><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1002603><P Class=KRCC>
괴델이 썼던 연습장입니다
<SYNC Start=1008103><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1008974><P Class=KRCC>
보시다시피 깔끔하고 정연합니다
<SYNC Start=1012178><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1013592><P Class=KRCC>
반면 이걸 볼까요
<SYNC Start=1014729><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1015128><P Class=KRCC>
연속체 가설을 연구하면서<br>
쓴 연습장입니다
<SYNC Start=1019031><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1023365><P Class=KRCC>
괴델은 칸토어와 마찬가지로<br>
이 문제를 풀지도, 내려놓지도 못했습니다<br>
<font color=magenta>(하지만 괴델은 나중에 이 문제의<br>
아주 중요한 진전을 이루었음)</font>
<SYNC Start=1029376><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1029649><P Class=KRCC>
상태가 점점 나빠졌는데도 말이죠
<SYNC Start=1032104><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1046371><P Class=KRCC>
여기에는 개인적, 심리적 차원의
<SYNC Start=1050001><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1050027><P Class=KRCC>
위험성이 도사리고 있습니다
<SYNC Start=1053411><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1054448><P Class=KRCC>
원래부터 지적 자기성찰이나<br>
자의식이 과잉이 되기 쉬운
<SYNC Start=1061013><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1061137><P Class=KRCC>
그런 성향의 사람일수록,
<SYNC Start=1064562><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1068828><P Class=KRCC>
학문 활동의 결과로<br>
그런 경향이 더욱 심화되어
<SYNC Start=1075523><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1075584><P Class=KRCC>
사는게 고달파질 수 있습니다
<SYNC Start=1078857><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1084058><P Class=KRCC>
괴델은 이때가 인생에서<br>
가장 불행한 때였다고 말했습니다
<SYNC Start=1086906><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1087261><P Class=KRCC>
그는 심각한 신경쇠약에 시달렸고<br>
결국 요양소로 향했습니다
<SYNC Start=1091071><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1091158><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어가 그랬듯이요
<SYNC Start=1093113><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1094700><P Class=KRCC>
물론 이건 능력이 뛰어나고
<SYNC Start=1098163><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1098194><P Class=KRCC>
극도로 추상적인<br>
문제들에 천착하면서
<SYNC Start=1103258><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1103445><P Class=KRCC>
자신을 잊어버릴 정도로<br>
몰입하다 보니
<SYNC Start=1107260><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1107741><P Class=KRCC>
스스로를 괴롭히는<br>
사람들의 얘기입니다
<SYNC Start=1111930><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1117653><P Class=KRCC>
이곳은 괴델이 지냈던<br>
요양소들 가운데 하나인
<SYNC Start=1121543><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1121660><P Class=KRCC>
비엔나 외곽의<br>
푸커스도르프 요양소입니다
<SYNC Start=1124871><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1126824><P Class=KRCC>
정신병은 이성주의를 통해<br>
치료할 수 있다는 것이
<SYNC Start=1130559><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1130673><P Class=KRCC>
이 요양소의<br>
건립 이념이었습니다
<SYNC Start=1135483><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1135823><P Class=KRCC>
이성의 한계를 시험했던 괴델이<br>
이곳에 오게 된 것은 아이러니입니다
<SYNC Start=1142493><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1146621><P Class=KRCC>
이성에 의한 확실성에 한계가 있음을<br>
보여준 인물이 이곳에 있던 동안
<SYNC Start=1152580><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1152750><P Class=KRCC>
바깥에서는 거대한 광기가<br>
퍼져나가고 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=1156574><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1156800><P Class=KRCC>
확실성을 부르짖는 선동가의 손에<br>
온 나라가 힘을 실어주고 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=1162731><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1174697><P Class=KRCC>
괴델의 정신병은 회복되었지만,<br>
오스트리아는 그렇지 못했습니다
<SYNC Start=1178700><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1178898><P Class=KRCC>
1939년 괴델은 나치 단원들에게<br>
공격을 당하기까지 했고
<SYNC Start=1183789><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1184253><P Class=KRCC>
결국 같은 해에 마지못해<br>
미국으로 떠났습니다
<SYNC Start=1189002><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1204189><P Class=KRCC>
전운이 감돌던 이 때에<br>
또다른 젊은 천재가 등장합니다
<SYNC Start=1208295><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1208428><P Class=KRCC>
앨런 튜링입니다
<SYNC Start=1211476><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1215810><P Class=KRCC>
튜링은 전쟁 중<br>
블레츨리 파크<font color=magenta>*</font>에서<br>
<font color=magenta>* 2차대전중 영국 암호 해독 부서의 애칭</font>
<SYNC Start=1219512><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1219573><P Class=KRCC>
독일의 이니그마<font color=magenta>*</font> 암호를<br>
해독한 것으로 유명합니다<br>
<font color=magenta>* 독일군이 사용했던 기계식 암호</font>
<SYNC Start=1222821><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1224795><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=yellow>- 이니그마(수수께끼) -</font>
<SYNC Start=1228899><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1231830><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 그는<br>
괴델의 불완전성 정리를
<SYNC Start=1235848><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1235891><P Class=KRCC>
더한층 나쁘게 확장시킨<br>
사람이기도 합니다
<SYNC Start=1239168><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1241221><P Class=KRCC>
그는 괴델보다 더 실용적인<br>
관점에서 접근했고
<SYNC Start=1244401><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1246724><P Class=KRCC>
괴델의 정리를 좀더 깔끔하게<br>
표현하려고 했습니다
<SYNC Start=1251138><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1251683><P Class=KRCC>
그 방법에 대한 연구는<br>
새로운 통찰을 낳았습니다
<SYNC Start=1255669><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1255922><P Class=KRCC>
바로 '컴퓨터'입니다
<SYNC Start=1258478><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1259503><P Class=KRCC>
사실은, 오늘날 세상을 바꾼<br>
컴퓨터의 발명도
<SYNC Start=1263858><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1264001><P Class=KRCC>
다소 추상적이고 와닿지 않는<br>
괴델의 불완전성 정리를
<SYNC Start=1269603><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1269775><P Class=KRCC>
뚜렷하게 구체화하려고 노력하는<br>
과정에서 생겨난 것입니다
<SYNC Start=1275254><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1275935><P Class=KRCC>
(괴델의 정리는) 수리철학적으로<br>
매우 큰 타격입니다
<SYNC Start=1280956><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1281072><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 증명 자체는 피상적이어서,<br>
구체적으로 어떤 함의가 있는지
<SYNC Start=1286191><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1286432><P Class=KRCC>
파악하기 어려웠습니다
<SYNC Start=1288189><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1288254><P Class=KRCC>
그런 타격을 줄만한<br>
이유라기엔 좀 약했달까요
<SYNC Start=1292726><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1292754><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>그레고리 채이틴 - 수학자, IBM 연구소</font><br>
괴델이 찾은 증명 불가능한 명제는<br>
지나치게 교묘하게 조작해낸 것이라서
<SYNC Start=1298007><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1298122><P Class=KRCC>
실질적으로 얼마나 심각한 문제인지<br>
감을 잡기가 어렵습니다
<SYNC Start=1301855><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1301926><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 5년 후<br>
튜링의 접근법이야말로
<SYNC Start=1307215><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1307362><P Class=KRCC>
불완전성을 더 잘 이해하는<br>
올바른 방향이었다고 봅니다
<SYNC Start=1311474><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1311876><P Class=KRCC>
튜링은 컴퓨터라는 관점에서<br>
불완전성을 바라보았으며
<SYNC Start=1315814><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1315954><P Class=KRCC>
컴퓨터 또한<br>
논리를 다루는 기계이므로
<SYNC Start=1319163><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1319339><P Class=KRCC>
불완전성은 컴퓨터가 풀지 못하는<br>
문제가 존재함을 의미합니다
<SYNC Start=1324438><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1324598><P Class=KRCC>
그러한 문제를 입력하면<br>
컴퓨터는 무한 루프에 빠지게 됩니다
<SYNC Start=1328740><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1328987><P Class=KRCC>
설상가상으로, 튜링은<br>
이러한 종류의 문제들을
<SYNC Start=1333662><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1333723><P Class=KRCC>
사전에 판별해내는 것은<br>
불가능함을 증명했습니다
<SYNC Start=1336836><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1340109><P Class=KRCC>
괴델은 모든 논리 체계에<br>
해결 불가능한 문제가 있음을 증명했습니다
<SYNC Start=1345649><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1345744><P Class=KRCC>
이것만도 나쁜 뉴스인데
<SYNC Start=1347553><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1347642><P Class=KRCC>
튜링은 불난 집에<br>
기름을 끼얹었습니다
<SYNC Start=1351177><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1351414><P Class=KRCC>
괴델까지만 해도, 증명 가능한 문제와<br>
불가능한 문제를 구별할 방법만 있다면
<SYNC Start=1357389><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1357541><P Class=KRCC>
증명 불가능한 문제는 회피할수 있는<br>
일말의 가능성이 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=1360888><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1361174><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 어떤 문제가<br>
증명 불가능한지의 여부를
<SYNC Start=1365060><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1365072><P Class=KRCC>
판별하는 일반적인 방법은<br>
없다는것을 튜링이 증명했습니다
<SYNC Start=1368696><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1369023><P Class=KRCC>
유한한 단계 내에 판정이 된다는<br>
보장이 없습니다
<SYNC Start=1372410><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1372638><P Class=KRCC>
주어진 문제가<br>
단지 아주 어려운 것인지
<SYNC Start=1377329><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1377554><P Class=KRCC>
애초에 증명이<br>
불가능한것인지 말이죠
<SYNC Start=1380109><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1380329><P Class=KRCC>
이것이 튜링의<br>
'정지(停止) 문제'입니다
<SYNC Start=1383973><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1384319><P Class=KRCC>
튜링의 설명은<br>
더 실제적인 방식입니다
<SYNC Start=1387801><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1387856><P Class=KRCC>
어떤 기계를 설정하고, 그 실행이<br>
종료되냐 아니냐에 대한 것이니까요
<SYNC Start=1391262><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1391384><P Class=KRCC>
그 논문에서는 딱히<br>
그런 표현을 쓰지는 않았지만
<SYNC Start=1395141><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1395190><P Class=KRCC>
기본 아이디어는 그렇습니다
<SYNC Start=1399043><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1399464><P Class=KRCC>
손에 잡히는<br>
컴퓨터에 대한 얘깁니다
<SYNC Start=1404641><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1404694><P Class=KRCC>
프로그램을 돌립니다,<br>
별도의 입출력은 없는 프로그램이죠..
<SYNC Start=1410208><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1410364><P Class=KRCC>
프로그램을 실행하면<br>
결과는 둘 중 하나입니다
<SYNC Start=1416109><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1416155><P Class=KRCC>
첫째, 언젠가는 실행을 종료하고
<SYNC Start=1418872><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1418932><P Class=KRCC>
답을 내놓고 끝, 이렇게 되거나
<SYNC Start=1422284><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1422396><P Class=KRCC>
둘째, 답을 찾으려고<br>
계속 실행하면서
<SYNC Start=1425414><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1425558><P Class=KRCC>
영원히 종료하지 않는겁니다.<br>
이렇게 둘 중 하나죠
<SYNC Start=1428762><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1429101><P Class=KRCC>
정리하면, "프로그램 실행이<br>
종료될지 아닌지 어떻게 알 수 있는가?"
<SYNC Start=1432726><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1432844><P Class=KRCC>
답은, "일반적인 판정 방법은 없다".<br>
이것이 불완전성의 튜링 버전입니다
<SYNC Start=1437819><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1437937><P Class=KRCC>
튜링은 괴델의 불완전성으로부터
<SYNC Start=1442095><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1442260><P Class=KRCC>
'계산 불가능성'이라는<br>
일반화시킨 개념을 만든 것이죠
<SYNC Start=1445837><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1445914><P Class=KRCC>
어떤 컴퓨터로도<br>
계산할 수 없다는 성질입니다
<SYNC Start=1449652><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1449840><P Class=KRCC>
특정 영역에서는 '대부분'의<br>
문제가 계산 불가능한데..
<SYNC Start=1452566><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1452718><P Class=KRCC>
그게 선생님이 연구하시는거죠?
<SYNC Start=1455194><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1455367><P Class=KRCC>
- 더욱 '나쁜' 결과로 확장하는..<br>
- 그냥 열심히 할 뿐이죠
<SYNC Start=1457646><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1457824><P Class=KRCC>
그중 일부는 이미 튜링의 논문에도<br>
있습니다. 그가 강조하진 않았지만..
<SYNC Start=1462701><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1464790><P Class=KRCC>
불완전성으로부터 착안한<br>
튜링의 심오한 물음은
<SYNC Start=1470980><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1471192><P Class=KRCC>
컴퓨터가 아닌<br>
우리의 정신에 관한 문제입니다
<SYNC Start=1477865><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1478333><P Class=KRCC>
인간의 두뇌는<br>
과연 컴퓨터일까요?
<SYNC Start=1481796><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1482294><P Class=KRCC>
그것은 튜링의 삶에서도<br>
중요한 의미를 갖는 질문입니다
<SYNC Start=1486569><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1487735><P Class=KRCC>
튜링에게는 각별히 사랑했던<br>
대상이 둘 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=1490203><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1490361><P Class=KRCC>
첫째는 크리스토퍼 모컴이라는<br>
남자였습니다
<SYNC Start=1494094><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1494668><P Class=KRCC>
둘째는 그가 세상에 내놓은<br>
컴퓨터입니다
<SYNC Start=1499425><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1501636><P Class=KRCC>
크리스토퍼를 향한 사랑은<br>
그에게 지울 수 없는 기억입니다
<SYNC Start=1505191><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1505603><P Class=KRCC>
그가 안타깝게도<br>
요절했기 때문이죠
<SYNC Start=1508378><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1508788><P Class=KRCC>
그는 순수한 첫사랑을<br>
영원히 잃었지만
<SYNC Start=1511406><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1511734><P Class=KRCC>
그 추억을 지워버리지도 않았습니다
<SYNC Start=1515331><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1518705><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 컴퓨터라는<br>
아이디어를 떠올린 뒤에는
<SYNC Start=1522107><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1522236><P Class=KRCC>
커다란 잠재력을 지닌<br>
컴퓨터와 사랑에 빠졌습니다
<SYNC Start=1528839><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1529210><P Class=KRCC>
그는 언젠가 컴퓨터가<br>
단순한 기계의 수준을 뛰어넘어
<SYNC Start=1535594><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1535890><P Class=KRCC>
사람처럼 배우고 생각하는 존재가<br>
될 수도 있다는 생각에 매혹되었습니다
<SYNC Start=1541443><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1541759><P Class=KRCC>
또한 과학자의 통찰력을 발휘하여,<br>
만일 인간의 정신도 컴퓨터와 같다면
<SYNC Start=1547302><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1547507><P Class=KRCC>
컴퓨터가 우리 자신을 이해하는<br>
훌륭한 도구라는 것을 깨달았습니다
<SYNC Start=1553149><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1555797><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어에서 시작된 무한에 대한<br>
순수 수학적인 질문은
<SYNC Start=1561034><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1561524><P Class=KRCC>
괴델에 의해 논리의 한계에 대한<br>
질문이 되었고
<SYNC Start=1564875><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1565274><P Class=KRCC>
튜링은 이것을 우리 인간 자신의<br>
정신에 대한 질문으로 바꾸었습니다
<SYNC Start=1572662><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1573031><P Class=KRCC>
튜링을 계산주의자<font color=magenta>*</font>로 보는<br>
시각이 일반적입니다<br>
<font color=magenta>* 인간의 두뇌가 본질적으로 컴퓨터와 동등한<br>
정보 처리 시스템이라고 보는 심리학적 견해</font>
<SYNC Start=1576681><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1576684><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>로저 펜로즈 - 수학자, 옥스포드 대학</font><br>
그가 그러한 입장을 취했던<br>
시기가 분명히 있습니다
<SYNC Start=1580889><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1581042><P Class=KRCC>
인간의 두뇌를 모방한 기계를<br>
만들 수도 있겠죠
<SYNC Start=1587037><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1587994><P Class=KRCC>
하지만 그는 컴퓨터의 한계를<br>
물론 잘 알고 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=1592281><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1592336><P Class=KRCC>
그것이 그의<br>
주요 업적이기도 하구요
<SYNC Start=1595297><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1595564><P Class=KRCC>
그가 중간에 입장을<br>
바꾸었을수도 있다고 봅니다
<SYNC Start=1601154><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1601182><P Class=KRCC>
그러다 컴퓨터를<br>
실제로 구현한 이후에는
<SYNC Start=1605227><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1605352><P Class=KRCC>
(계산주의가) 아마도 옳은 방향이라고<br>
생각했을것도 같습니다
<SYNC Start=1608730><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1608790><P Class=KRCC>
자신이 지지하는 과학 이론에<br>
완전히 빠져들게 되면
<SYNC Start=1613207><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1613244><P Class=KRCC>
"이것이 모든 문제를 풀 수 있는 답이야"<br>
라고 생각하기 쉽죠
<SYNC Start=1616412><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1616570><P Class=KRCC>
그 이론에 이미 내재된 한계를<br>
실감하지 못하고 말입니다
<SYNC Start=1622057><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1623198><P Class=KRCC>
튜링은 자신과 괴델의 연구의<br>
의미를 알고 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=1627279><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1627432><P Class=KRCC>
즉, 인간의 두뇌가 컴퓨터라면<br>
마찬가지로 불완전성의 적용 대상이므로
<SYNC Start=1632558><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1632836><P Class=KRCC>
따라서 논리학의 한계는<br>
곧 인간 정신의 한계를 뜻하며
<SYNC Start=1636764><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1637029><P Class=KRCC>
인간은 논리 추론의 한계를<br>
초월할수 없다는 것을 말입니다
<SYNC Start=1641583><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1642060><P Class=KRCC>
사실, 튜링의 수학 이론이 그의<br>
개인적 철학과 일치할 필요는 없죠
<SYNC Start=1647351><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1647597><P Class=KRCC>
인공지능에 관한<br>
그의 저작을 보면
<SYNC Start=1652222><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1652290><P Class=KRCC>
그는 기계도 인간처럼.. 더 낫든, 다르든,<br>
어쨌든 '지능'을 가질수 있다고 믿었습니다
<SYNC Start=1659053><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1659254><P Class=KRCC>
그런데, 첫번째 논문을 보면<br>
기계의 한계를 지적하고 있습니다
<SYNC Start=1664466><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1664628><P Class=KRCC>
대부분의 수는 어떠한 기계로도<br>
계산할수 없다는 증명을 통해서 말이죠<br>
<font color=gray>(수리논리학에서 말하는 '수를 계산한다'는<br>
개념은 일상적으로 말하는 숫자 계산과 다름)</font>
<SYNC Start=1669425><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1669605><P Class=KRCC>
그러나, 튜링 자신이 벌써
<SYNC Start=1671464><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1671486><P Class=KRCC>
기계의 한계를 초월하는<br>
인간의 상상력을 과시하고 있죠
<SYNC Start=1676593><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1676775><P Class=KRCC>
튜링의 철학적 견해와 상반되죠.<br>
그가 스스로를 '기계'라고 생각했을지라도,
<SYNC Start=1680673><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1680778><P Class=KRCC>
그 자신이 바로 첫 논문에서부터<br>
컴퓨터라는 개념을 창조해 내고
<SYNC Start=1685404><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1685431><P Class=KRCC>
그것의 명백한 한계를<br>
통렬하게 지적하고 있으니까요
<SYNC Start=1689521><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1690824><P Class=KRCC>
튜링도 이 딜레마를 알았지만
<SYNC Start=1693254><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1693338><P Class=KRCC>
인간의 정신을 기계적 계산으로 환원하여<br>
설명하는데 전력을 다했습니다
<SYNC Start=1700224><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1700510><P Class=KRCC>
그것은 과학자로서의<br>
바람만은 아니었습니다
<SYNC Start=1704733><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1705306><P Class=KRCC>
튜링이 늘 가졌던 신념은<br>
위선과 기만,
<SYNC Start=1709278><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1709323><P Class=KRCC>
비굴한 타협으로부터<br>
자유로운 삶이었습니다
<SYNC Start=1713060><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1713369><P Class=KRCC>
튜링은 동성애자였고, 그때는<br>
이것이 위험한 불법행위였습니다
<SYNC Start=1717696><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1717762><P Class=KRCC>
그는 그것을 특별히 감추지도<br>
드러내지도 않았습니다
<SYNC Start=1721239><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1725355><P Class=KRCC>
컴퓨터는 거짓이나 위선을 모릅니다
<SYNC Start=1729278><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1729545><P Class=KRCC>
우리가 컴퓨터였다면, 우리는<br>
튜링이 원했던 모습의 존재였을겁니다
<SYNC Start=1736087><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1738157><P Class=KRCC>
누구나 마음을 바꿀 수 있죠.<br>
자신의 생각을 돌아보고
<SYNC Start=1741305><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1741310><P Class=KRCC>
이게 정말 맞는걸까 되묻거나<br>
다른 생각으로 갈아타기도 하죠
<SYNC Start=1744199><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1744207><P Class=KRCC>
좋은 과학자라면 무턱대고<br>
하나의 관점에만 집착하지 않아요
<SYNC Start=1749882><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1749945><P Class=KRCC>
그래서 저는 튜링의 마음도<br>
흔들리지 않았을까 합니다
<SYNC Start=1753051><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1753122><P Class=KRCC>
하지만 제 생각에<br>
튜링은 자신의 관점에 대한..
<SYNC Start=1757970><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1757979><P Class=KRCC>
.. 다른이들의 비판을<br>
분석하고 허점을 찾아내서
<SYNC Start=1761891><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1762038><P Class=KRCC>
이렇게 반박하려<br>
했을수도 있죠
<SYNC Start=1764716><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1764905><P Class=KRCC>
"계산 불가능성에 대한<br>
정리에도 불구하고.."
<SYNC Start=1769550><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1769619><P Class=KRCC>
"..논증에서 이러이러한<br>
빠져나갈 구멍이 있으니까.."
<SYNC Start=1772849><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1772871><P Class=KRCC>
"..어쨌든 인간의 정신은<br>
컴퓨터와 동등한 것일수도 있다."
<SYNC Start=1776017><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1776139><P Class=KRCC>
이런 빠져나갈 구멍만 있어도<br>
스스로 만족했는지도 모릅니다
<SYNC Start=1780330><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1780537><P Class=KRCC>
또 튜링 머신<font color=magenta>*</font>보다 강력한<br>
오라클 머신<font color=magenta>**</font>에 대한 연구도 했습니다<br>
<font color=magenta>* 튜링 머신 = 튜링이 제안한 계산의 수학적 모델.<br>
컴퓨터의 핵심 개념을 추상화시킨 것으로 보면 됨</font>
<SYNC Start=1786456><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1786545><P Class=KRCC>
우리가 접할 수 있는<br>
보통 컴퓨터와는 다른것이죠<br>
<font color=magenta>** 오라클 머신 = 튜링 머신에 가상적인<br>
능력을 추가시킨 것. 수학적 분석에 쓰임
<SYNC Start=1790877><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1791287><P Class=KRCC>
이론적인 개념일 뿐이지만
<SYNC Start=1793464><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1793682><P Class=KRCC>
일반적인 컴퓨터의<br>
능력을 넘는 이론적 기계입니다
<SYNC Start=1799548><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1803186><P Class=KRCC>
튜링은 이렇게 인간과<br>
계산 기계 사이에서 갈등했습니다
<SYNC Start=1808967><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1809296><P Class=KRCC>
이윽고 그를 죽음에 이르게 한<br>
사건이 터졌습니다
<SYNC Start=1813841><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1817156><P Class=KRCC>
전쟁 후 튜링은 국가정보부의<br>
주시 대상이 되었습니다
<SYNC Start=1823362><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1823886><P Class=KRCC>
냉전 하에서 동성애는<br>
부도덕한 불법 행위일뿐 아니라
<SYNC Start=1829500><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1829552><P Class=KRCC>
안보에 대한 위협으로<br>
간주되었기 때문입니다
<SYNC Start=1832897><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1835752><P Class=KRCC>
튜링은 1952년 3월 동성애 행위로<br>
체포되어 유죄판결을 받았고
<SYNC Start=1843924><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1844106><P Class=KRCC>
당국은 그를 교정이 필요한<br>
문제 인물로 지목했습니다
<SYNC Start=1849322><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1849974><P Class=KRCC>
여성 호르몬 에스트로겐을 주사하여<br>
화학적 거세를 시도했습니다
<SYNC Start=1856287><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1857336><P Class=KRCC>
튜링은 인간이 아닌<br>
기계 취급을 당한 것입니다
<SYNC Start=1860356><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1860575><P Class=KRCC>
성 정체성의 불확실성 및<br>
안보와 질서에 대한 위협을 제거하려고
<SYNC Start=1865890><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1865894><P Class=KRCC>
화학적으로 다시 프로그램된<br>
기계 말입니다
<SYNC Start=1870203><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1871395><P Class=KRCC>
이 요법은 끔찍하게도<br>
그의 몸과 마음을 망가뜨렸습니다
<SYNC Start=1876179><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1876498><P Class=KRCC>
유방이 부풀어올랐고<br>
정신상태는 불안정해졌습니다
<SYNC Start=1881827><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1882561><P Class=KRCC>
언제나 바르게 살았던 그에게는
<SYNC Start=1886426><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1886466><P Class=KRCC>
'위선'이라는 주사를<br>
맞은 것이나 다름없었습니다
<SYNC Start=1890598><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1894264><P Class=KRCC>
1954년 6월 7일<br>
튜링은 사망했습니다
<SYNC Start=1898610><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1898970><P Class=KRCC>
몇 입 깨문 사과가<br>
그의 곁에 놓여 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=1903667><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1903976><P Class=KRCC>
튜링이 스스로 청산가리를<br>
사과에 주입한 것입니다
<SYNC Start=1907334><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1914026><P Class=KRCC>
튜링은 떠났지만,<br>
그의 물음은 남았습니다
<SYNC Start=1917995><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1918345><P Class=KRCC>
인간은 컴퓨터처럼 한계가 있는가,<br>
아니면 논리의 한계를 넘을수 있는가?
<SYNC Start=1924792><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1925087><P Class=KRCC>
이 물음은 이제<br>
괴델의 고민이 되었습니다
<SYNC Start=1929529><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1932307><P Class=KRCC>
괴델은 이때 미국으로 와<br>
고등과학원에 있었고
<SYNC Start=1936644><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1936727><P Class=KRCC>
지나칠 정도로 열심히<br>
연구에 매달렸습니다
<SYNC Start=1940466><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1947579><P Class=KRCC>
물론 이때의 괴델은<br>
정신병에서 회복되었지만
<SYNC Start=1950514><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1950681><P Class=KRCC>
이곳에서의 그는<br>
아주 유별난 사람이었다고 합니다
<SYNC Start=1956446><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1961522><P Class=KRCC>
한 예로 소문에 의하면
<SYNC Start=1963325><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1963440><P Class=KRCC>
사람이 많은 곳에서는<br>
타인과 신체 접촉을 꺼려하여
<SYNC Start=1968536><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1968683><P Class=KRCC>
가만히 선 채로<br>
쏙 빠져나갈 길을 찾은 다음
<SYNC Start=1972719><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1972827><P Class=KRCC>
누구와도 부딪치지 않고<br>
지나갔다고 합니다
<SYNC Start=1975289><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1975476><P Class=KRCC>
냉난방 장치에서 나오는<br>
'나쁜 공기'에
<SYNC Start=1978760><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1978830><P Class=KRCC>
자신이 중독되고 있다고 느꼈으며
<SYNC Start=1980887><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1981052><P Class=KRCC>
심지어 자기의 음식에<br>
독이 들었다고 생각했습니다
<SYNC Start=1983563><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1983840><P Class=KRCC>
아내에게 모든 음식을<br>
먼저 시식해달라고 했고
<SYNC Start=1987385><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1987536><P Class=KRCC>
한번은 오렌지를 주문한 다음<br>
독이 들었다며 반품하기도 했습니다
<SYNC Start=1992510><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1996538><P Class=KRCC>
기인이 되어 버렸지만<br>
그의 천재성은 죽지 않았습니다
<SYNC Start=2001134><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2001348><P Class=KRCC>
튜링과 달리, 괴델은<br>
인간이 컴퓨터라고 믿지 않았습니다
<SYNC Start=2006078><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2006381><P Class=KRCC>
그는 인간이 논리학의 한계를<br>
어떻게 뛰어넘을수 있는지
<SYNC Start=2011168><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2011413><P Class=KRCC>
또는 그렇지 못한다면 어떻게 될지<br>
알아내려고 했습니다
<SYNC Start=2014276><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2015302><P Class=KRCC>
이론상, 주어진 공리들로부터<br>
기계적인 과정으로
<SYNC Start=2018693><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2018715><P Class=KRCC>
모든 논리적 귀결을<br>
생성할수 있다고 상상해 보면,
<SYNC Start=2021358><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2021401><P Class=KRCC>
수학은 생명력이 없는<br>
정적인 세계일겁니다
<SYNC Start=2023199><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2023203><P Class=KRCC>
정리를 유도하는<br>
기계적인 과정이 전부라면
<SYNC Start=2027238><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2027284><P Class=KRCC>
결국 수학자도<br>
일종의 기계에 불과하죠
<SYNC Start=2032017><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2032250><P Class=KRCC>
제 생각엔, 튜링은<br>
스스로를 기계라고 생각했습니다
<SYNC Start=2035649><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2035762><P Class=KRCC>
'흉내내기 게임'<font color=magenta>*</font>에 관한 논문으로<br>
미루어 알 수 있죠<br>
<font color=magenta>* 인공 지능을 판별하는 테스트.<br>
지금은 '튜링 테스트'라고 부름</font>
<SYNC Start=2041472><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2041672><P Class=KRCC>
괴델은 스스로를<br>
기계로 간주하지 않았고
<SYNC Start=2044192><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2044226><P Class=KRCC>
인간에게는 어떤 신성한<br>
창의성이 있기 때문에
<SYNC Start=2048217><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2048254><P Class=KRCC>
새로운 수학을<br>
창조해낼 수 있다고 믿었죠
<SYNC Start=2051029><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2052621><P Class=KRCC>
인간만이 지닌 창의성을<br>
그가 확신했던 까닭은 무엇일까요?
<SYNC Start=2057525><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2058023><P Class=KRCC>
그것은 그의 절친한 친구<br>
한 명과 공감했던
<SYNC Start=2061562><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2061574><P Class=KRCC>
어떤 철학적 확신에서<br>
기인합니다
<SYNC Start=2064899><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2065220><P Class=KRCC>
고등과학원에 있었던<br>
또다른 오스트리아인 천재
<SYNC Start=2069883><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2069959><P Class=KRCC>
알베르트 아인슈타인입니다
<SYNC Start=2071942><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2073916><P Class=KRCC>
아인슈타인은 괴델과 함께<br>
산책하는 특권을 누리고 싶어서
<SYNC Start=2077739><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2077787><P Class=KRCC>
고등과학원으로 온 것이라고<br>
말하곤 했습니다
<SYNC Start=2080703><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2081001><P Class=KRCC>
판이한 이 두 사람이<br>
친밀했던 이유는 무엇일까요?
<SYNC Start=2083847><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2084078><P Class=KRCC>
아저씨처럼 푸근한 아인슈타인과
<SYNC Start=2086687><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2086734><P Class=KRCC>
재미없고 야윈 내성적인 괴델.
<SYNC Start=2090968><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2091221><P Class=KRCC>
저는 아인슈타인이 했던<br>
이 말에 주목합니다
<SYNC Start=2094120><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2094304><P Class=KRCC>
"신(神)은 이해하기 까다롭지만,<br>
심술궂은 존재는 아니다."
<SYNC Start=2098552><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2098789><P Class=KRCC>
이것은 비유적인 표현으로,
<SYNC Start=2101337><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2101380><P Class=KRCC>
우주가 아무리 복잡해 보이더라도<br>
반드시 아름다운 법칙이 있다는 말입니다
<SYNC Start=2107602><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2108070><P Class=KRCC>
괴델의 철학도 같았습니다,<br>
다시 말하면
<SYNC Start=2111914><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2112112><P Class=KRCC>
신은 인간에게 절대 불가해한 세상을<br>
창조하지는 않았다는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=2116843><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2117359><P Class=KRCC>
그런데, 논리적 증명의 한계를<br>
밝혀낸 괴델 자신이 어떻게
<SYNC Start=2122992><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2123145><P Class=KRCC>
신이 심술궂지 않으며, 세상은<br>
이해할수 있는 것이라고 믿었을까요?
<SYNC Start=2130055><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2130743><P Class=KRCC>
신은 사악하다고 했어야<br>
하지 않을까요?
<SYNC Start=2133499><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2134066><P Class=KRCC>
그 답은, 아인슈타인처럼 괴델도<br>
직관의 가치를 높이 샀기 때문일겁니다
<SYNC Start=2139158><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2139293><P Class=KRCC>
인간이 가진 직관의 힘으로<br>
논리의 한계를 넘을수 있다는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=2144791><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2145113><P Class=KRCC>
탁월한 직관의 순간을 경험했던<br>
두 사람 모두, 그 점을 믿었습니다
<SYNC Start=2149968><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2150260><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어처럼 말이죠
<SYNC Start=2151772><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2152016><P Class=KRCC>
그가 제안한<br>
수학자의 행동 원리는..
<SYNC Start=2157383><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2157448><P Class=KRCC>
눈을 감고,<br>
자아를 세상과 단절시키고,
<SYNC Start=2160406><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2160524><P Class=KRCC>
수학적 직관력을 이용하여 직접<br>
플라톤적 이데아의 세계를 인식하고
<SYNC Start=2165552><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2165621><P Class=KRCC>
거기서 이끌어낸 새로운 원리로
<SYNC Start=2168188><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2168232><P Class=KRCC>
수학을 발전시키는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=2171679><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2171902><P Class=KRCC>
이렇게 괴델은 불완전성 정리가<br>
인간의 한계를 뜻하지 않으며
<SYNC Start=2175393><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2175468><P Class=KRCC>
인간이 만들수 있는 수학의 한계는<br>
없다고 생각했다고, 저는 판단합니다
<SYNC Start=2179898><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2180188><P Class=KRCC>
이 주장을 입증할수 있을까요?
<SYNC Start=2181714><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2181822><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>카를 지그문트 - 수학자, 비엔나 대학</font><br>
괴델 자신도 컴퓨터의 한계라는<br>
해석을 끌어냈습니다
<SYNC Start=2190847><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2191339><P Class=KRCC>
그는 인간 정신이 컴퓨터를<br>
초월한다는 사실을 밝혀내려고
<SYNC Start=2196239><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2196257><P Class=KRCC>
끊임없이 시도했습니다
<SYNC Start=2199526><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2199796><P Class=KRCC>
컴퓨터 프로그램으로<br>
증명하기 어려운 진리도
<SYNC Start=2204591><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2204633><P Class=KRCC>
그는 이해할 수 있었으니까요
<SYNC Start=2207498><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2207780><P Class=KRCC>
괴델은 경험이나<br>
수학적 논증보다는
<SYNC Start=2213452><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2213559><P Class=KRCC>
직관을 통해 진리를 추구하는<br>
방법에 대해 고민했습니다
<SYNC Start=2219909><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2220253><P Class=KRCC>
그는 자신의 이론을 잘못 이해한<br>
사람들에게 실망했습니다
<SYNC Start=2224085><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2224457><P Class=KRCC>
어째서인지 많은 사람들이<br>
괴델의 의도를 오해하고 있습니다
<SYNC Start=2230247><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2230711><P Class=KRCC>
괴델은 사려깊은 방식으로
<SYNC Start=2233828><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2233931><P Class=KRCC>
그가 생각하는 의미의<br>
수학적 직관을 놓고
<SYNC Start=2238804><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2238854><P Class=KRCC>
직관은 형식적인 규칙만 따라가는<br>
추론의 범주 밖에 있음을
<SYNC Start=2243394><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2243473><P Class=KRCC>
보여주려고 했습니다
<SYNC Start=2246523><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2247112><P Class=KRCC>
어떤이들은 괴델의 말을<br>
엉뚱하게 곡해해서
<SYNC Start=2250996><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2251196><P Class=KRCC>
"증명불가능한 진리가 존재하며, 이것들은<br>
인간 정신이 닿을수 없는 영역에 있다."
<SYNC Start=2254142><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2254478><P Class=KRCC>
이렇게들 말하는데, 원래 의미는,<br>
어떤 논리 체계를 채택하더라도..
<SYNC Start=2259309><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2259425><P Class=KRCC>
아, 그리고 그 체계를<br>
인간이 정했지만
<SYNC Start=2262087><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2262122><P Class=KRCC>
정해 놓은 다음에는<br>
정신과는 별개의 문제이죠..
<SYNC Start=2265402><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2265521><P Class=KRCC>
어쨌든 여기서부터,<br>
"이 체계의 범위가 어디까지이냐?"
<SYNC Start=2269558><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2269776><P Class=KRCC>
괴델의 답은, 어느 체계에든<br>
반드시 한계가 있고
<SYNC Start=2272499><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2272516><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 인간 정신은<br>
그 제약에서 자유롭다는 겁니다
<SYNC Start=2274522><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2274816><P Class=KRCC>
괴델은 모든 논리 체계에는 그 안에<br>
증명 불가능한 명제가 있음을 증명했습니다
<SYNC Start=2281609><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2281830><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 인간에겐 직관이 있으니<br>
그 제한이 문제가 되지 않는다고 했습니다
<SYNC Start=2286774><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2287525><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 이 설명이 말이 되려면<br>
'직관'이라는 존재를 입증해야 하는데
<SYNC Start=2293761><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2294086><P Class=KRCC>
그것이 결코 쉬울리가 없죠
<SYNC Start=2296733><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2297058><P Class=KRCC>
그가 자신의 견해를 강하게 주장했던<br>
논문 초안이 있는데
<SYNC Start=2301982><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2302057><P Class=KRCC>
괴델 자신도 불만족스러워했습니다
<SYNC Start=2304716><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2304789><P Class=KRCC>
창의성이나 직관 같은건<br>
증명할수가 없기 때문이죠
<SYNC Start=2307364><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2307401><P Class=KRCC>
그냥 '감'에 불과하니까요
<SYNC Start=2312046><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2313066><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어가 그랬듯이
<SYNC Start=2316081><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2316145><P Class=KRCC>
괴델도 어떻게든 풀고 싶지만<br>
풀수없는 문제에 부딪쳤습니다
<SYNC Start=2321623><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2322102><P Class=KRCC>
쉽게 빠져나올수 없는<br>
논리의 쳇바퀴에 갇혀 버렸습니다
<SYNC Start=2328224><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2328972><P Class=KRCC>
동시에 스스로를 서서히<br>
굶겨 죽이기 시작했습니다
<SYNC Start=2333154><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2338291><P Class=KRCC>
수학의 한계를 수학을 이용하여<br>
입증한다는건 일면 이율배반적이죠
<SYNC Start=2346011><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2348008><P Class=KRCC>
괴델도 분명히<br>
이것을 잘 알고 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=2352566><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2353689><P Class=KRCC>
그 자신의 삶도 역설적이었죠
<SYNC Start=2355959><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2356066><P Class=KRCC>
대상으로 그 대상 자신을<br>
분석하는 일입니다
<SYNC Start=2361465><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2372771><P Class=KRCC>
누군가는 '현대의 현기증'이라고<br>
표현했던 것인데
<SYNC Start=2375572><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2375599><P Class=KRCC>
그런 재귀적인 소용돌이 속으로<br>
빠져드는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=2379539><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2379600><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>루이스 새스 - 임상심리학자, 럿거스 대학</font><br>
생각에 대해 생각하는 것에 대해<br>
생각하는 것에 대해 생각하는..
<SYNC Start=2382989><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2383140><P Class=KRCC>
자기만의 생각 속에<br>
말려드는 것이죠
<SYNC Start=2387769><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2389852><P Class=KRCC>
저는 이것이 현대(現代)의<br>
본질이 아닌가 생각합니다
<SYNC Start=2393830><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2393984><P Class=KRCC>
'자기 관찰의 역설'이라고<br>
부를만한 것이니까요
<SYNC Start=2398739><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2399136><P Class=KRCC>
모더니즘과 연관되어 있는<br>
종류의 광기는<br>
<SYNC Start=2404583><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2404607><P Class=KRCC>
이성적 활동에서<br>
기인하는 것 뿐만 아니라
<SYNC Start=2410665><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2410684><P Class=KRCC>
자의식, 그러니까<br>
의식적인 자아를 스스로 관찰하고
<SYNC Start=2415808><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2415934><P Class=KRCC>
논리 자체를 논리로써<br>
분석하는데서 나오는 역설입니다
<SYNC Start=2419246><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2421579><P Class=KRCC>
그 자신이 논리의 한계를<br>
밝히긴 했지만
<SYNC Start=2425077><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2425124><P Class=KRCC>
그래도 여전히 합리성과 논리를<br>
중시했기 때문에
<SYNC Start=2430917><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2431133><P Class=KRCC>
논리적으로 중요한 결과를<br>
증명하려고 사력을 다했습니다
<SYNC Start=2435081><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2435154><P Class=KRCC>
논리가 아닌<br>
다른 대안이라도 말이죠
<SYNC Start=2437553><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2438238><P Class=KRCC>
논리적 증명에 대한<br>
집착으로부터
<SYNC Start=2444481><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2444664><P Class=KRCC>
괴델 자신이 자유롭지<br>
못했다는 반증입니다
<SYNC Start=2449795><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2458311><P Class=KRCC>
우리 이야기의 처음에서,<br>
칸토어는 수학의 맨 밑바닥에
<SYNC Start=2463854><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2464056><P Class=KRCC>
'신의 마음'인 확실성이<br>
자리하고 있을거라 믿었습니다
<SYNC Start=2469911><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2470250><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 의도와는 다르게<br>
불확실성을 들추어냈고
<SYNC Start=2473890><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2475195><P Class=KRCC>
튜링과 괴델은 이것이<br>
사라지지 않을것임을 증명했습니다
<SYNC Start=2479117><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2479320><P Class=KRCC>
불확실성은 수학과 논리의 토대를<br>
이루는 피할 수 없는 존재입니다
<SYNC Start=2484785><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2490891><P Class=KRCC>
확실성의 세계를 지배하는<br>
완벽한 논리가 있을 것이라는
<SYNC Start=2495748><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2495830><P Class=KRCC>
거의 종교에 가까운 믿음은<br>
깨어졌습니다
<SYNC Start=2500475><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2501053><P Class=KRCC>
논리의 한계가<br>
논리에 의해 드러났고
<SYNC Start=2504609><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2504827><P Class=KRCC>
확실성을 향한 추구에서<br>
불확실성이 드러났습니다
<SYNC Start=2509027><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2510319><P Class=KRCC>
다른 사람들이<br>
어떻게 생각할지 모르지만
<SYNC Start=2513097><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2513146><P Class=KRCC>
제가 생각하는<br>
하나의 해법은 뭐냐면
<SYNC Start=2516610><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2516784><P Class=KRCC>
잘 안보이게<br>
살짝 덮어두는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=2519718><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2519744><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 이건 문제를<br>
푸는건 아니죠
<SYNC Start=2521552><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2521703><P Class=KRCC>
사실, 문제를 끼고 사는게<br>
더 재미있지 않겠어요?
<SYNC Start=2524386><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2524683><P Class=KRCC>
창의성의 여지가 있잖아요
<SYNC Start=2526408><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2528404><P Class=KRCC>
절대적 확실성이라..<br>
인간의 삶에 그런건 없습니다
<SYNC Start=2534157><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2534380><P Class=KRCC>
세상에 대해 우리가<br>
가질 수 있는 지식은
<SYNC Start=2538985><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2539089><P Class=KRCC>
불완전하고 유한합니다.<br>
우리가 그러한 존재이니까요
<SYNC Start=2543335><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2544084><P Class=KRCC>
오늘날에도, 어떤 지식들은<br>
너무 위험한 것이라고 여겨집니다
<SYNC Start=2549825><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2550201><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어, 볼츠만, 괴델의 시대에서<br>
별로 달라진게 없는듯도 합니다
<SYNC Start=2555952><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2565583><P Class=KRCC>
우리들도 역시,<br>
굳게 믿었던 대상은 도전받고
<SYNC Start=2570366><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2570471><P Class=KRCC>
확실성은 미끄러져 나갑니다
<SYNC Start=2573552><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2573933><P Class=KRCC>
예전과 다름없이 우리는<br>
확실성에 대한 믿음을 꼭 쥐고
<SYNC Start=2580171><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2580491><P Class=KRCC>
위안을 얻으려 합니다
<SYNC Start=2582378><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2585264><P Class=KRCC>
제 생각에<br>
우리에게 남겨진 질문은
<SYNC Start=2589411><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2589492><P Class=KRCC>
칸토어나 볼츠만의 때와<br>
다르지 않습니다
<SYNC Start=2593225><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2593514><P Class=KRCC>
지금 우리는 불확실성과 함께<br>
살아갈수 있을만큼 성숙할까요?
<SYNC Start=2597341><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2597546><P Class=KRCC>
아니면 우리는 지난 세기의<br>
실수를 되풀이하며
<SYNC Start=2601060><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2601261><P Class=KRCC>
맹목적으로 또다른 확실성을<br>
찾고 있는 것일까요?
<SYNC Start=2606341><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2615000><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=orange>딕테이션, 한/영 자막 제작<br>
DCinside 과학갤/다큐갤 '디핑'<br>
croydon.egloos.com</font>
<SYNC Start=2620000><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;

<SYNC Start=4590><P Class=ENCC>
But by the beginning of the 1900s, the struggle was getting too hard for him.
<SYNC Start=9819><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=12554><P Class=ENCC>
Boltzmann had discovered one of the fundamental equations
<SYNC Start=15877><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=16029><P Class=ENCC>
which makes the universe work, and he had dedicated his life to it.
<SYNC Start=19999><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=20800><P Class=ENCC>
The philosopher Bertrand Russell said that "For any great thinker.."
<SYNC Start=24419><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=24603><P Class=ENCC>
"..this discovery that everything flows from these fundamental laws comes.."
<SYNC Start=28702><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=28813><P Class=ENCC>
as he described it, "..with the overwhelming force of a revelation, .."
<SYNC Start=33695><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=35353><P Class=ENCC>
"..like a palace emerging from the autumn mist, .."
<SYNC Start=38669><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=38708><P Class=ENCC>
"..as the traveler ascends the Italian hillside."
<SYNC Start=42500><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=45150><P Class=ENCC>
And so it was for Boltzmann.
<SYNC Start=46955><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=47021><P Class=ENCC>
But for him, that palace was here at Duino in Italy,
<SYNC Start=51457><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=51535><P Class=ENCC>
where he hung himself.
<SYNC Start=54197><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=57848><P Class=ENCC>
In 1906, Boltzmann came here to Duino with his wife and daughter on holiday,
<SYNC Start=64184><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=65175><P Class=ENCC>
.. exhausted and demoralized, his ideas still not accepted.
<SYNC Start=70057><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=70373><P Class=ENCC>
While they were out walking he killed himself and left no note of explanation.
<SYNC Start=76858><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=96937><P Class=ENCC>
Of course we can never know what Boltzmann was thinking, but I think we have clues.
<SYNC Start=101798><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=102447><P Class=ENCC>
Boltzmann knew what it was to be in the grip of a beautiful and powerful idea.
<SYNC Start=107329><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=107443><P Class=ENCC>
He once wrote that "What is the poet laments holds for the mathematician.."
<SYNC Start=112177><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=112323><P Class=ENCC>
".. that he writes his works with the blood of his heart."
<SYNC Start=115943><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=116207><P Class=ENCC>
So we know that he was a passionate man.
<SYNC Start=118815><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=123931><P Class=ENCC>
But I think there is another clue.
<SYNC Start=125792><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=126322><P Class=ENCC>
At the start of one of Boltzmann's major scientific papers
<SYNC Start=129184><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=129347><P Class=ENCC>
he quotes three lines from Goethe's 'Faust'.
<SYNC Start=132642><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=132936><P Class=ENCC>
"Bring forth what is true. Write it so it's clear. Defend it to your last breath."
<SYNC Start=138143><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=138286><P Class=ENCC>
.. which of course of he does.
<SYNC Start=139935><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=140192><P Class=ENCC>
But I think there's something deeper here.
<SYNC Start=142272><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=142448><P Class=ENCC>
Why quote 'Faust' at the start of a scientific paper?
<SYNC Start=147066><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=148752><P Class=ENCC>
The pact that Faust makes with the Devil
<SYNC Start=152478><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=152584><P Class=ENCC>
is that the devil will give him of all of the knowledge and all of the experience that he wants,
<SYNC Start=157672><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=157724><P Class=ENCC>
so long as he never asks to stay in any one moment.
<SYNC Start=164297><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=164732><P Class=ENCC>
And I think when Boltzmann came here to this beautiful place
<SYNC Start=168920><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=169076><P Class=ENCC>
after thirty years of fighting for what he believed in,
<SYNC Start=172731><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=173228><P Class=ENCC>
He simply said,
<SYNC Start=175239><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=175425><P Class=ENCC>
"I want to stay here in this perfect beautiful moment."
<SYNC Start=179851><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=180102><P Class=ENCC>
"I don't want to have to leave. I want time for me to stop."
<SYNC Start=186649><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=188965><P Class=ENCC>
The great and controversial thing that Boltzmann had done
<SYNC Start=192478><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=192557><P Class=ENCC>
was to introduce into the unchanging perfection of classical physics
<SYNC Start=197094><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=197174><P Class=ENCC>
the notion of real time, of irreversible change.
<SYNC Start=201215><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=201469><P Class=ENCC>
And yet it was this man, who in his final moments wanted time to stop.
<SYNC Start=207368><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=216971><P Class=ENCC>
So ironically Boltzmann was vindicated just after his death.
<SYNC Start=221401><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=221591><P Class=ENCC>
If he would have waited a little longer, Boltzmann would have been
<SYNC Start=225871><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=226092><P Class=ENCC>
one of the father of the revolutionary of the 20th century physics.
<SYNC Start=232545><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=234236><P Class=ENCC>
Yet Boltzmann died as he'd lived, out of step with his times.
<SYNC Start=238700><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=238905><P Class=ENCC>
He had sown the seeds of uncertainty in physics,
<SYNC Start=241961><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=242020><P Class=ENCC>
but no school of followers took up his work.
<SYNC Start=244433><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=245101><P Class=ENCC>
Against all the odds it was Cantor, who had uncovered uncertainty in mathematics,
<SYNC Start=249881><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=249963><P Class=ENCC>
around whom followers were gathering.
<SYNC Start=252531><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=253256><P Class=ENCC>
A new generation of mathematicians and philosophers were convinced
<SYNC Start=257223><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=257392><P Class=ENCC>
if only they could solve the problems and paradoxes that had defeated Cantor
<SYNC Start=262163><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=262375><P Class=ENCC>
math could be made perfect again.
<SYNC Start=265561><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=268961><P Class=ENCC>
The most prominent amongst them, Hilbert, declared
<SYNC Start=272778><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=273015><P Class=ENCC>
"The definitive clarification of the nature of the infinite.."
<SYNC Start=276548><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=276683><P Class=ENCC>
"..has become necessary for the honour of human understanding itself."
<SYNC Start=281608><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=282944><P Class=ENCC>
They were so concerned to find some kind of certainty,
<SYNC Start=286361><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=286488><P Class=ENCC>
they'd come to believe that the only kind of understanding
<SYNC Start=289034><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=289068><P Class=ENCC>
that was really worth anything was the logical and the provable.
<SYNC Start=293036><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=293759><P Class=ENCC>
And a measure of how desperate this attempt to find
<SYNC Start=296750><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=296799><P Class=ENCC>
the perfect system of reasoning and logic had become is this.
<SYNC Start=301240><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=301485><P Class=ENCC>
Three volumes of the 'Principia Mathematica' published in 1910.
<SYNC Start=305903><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=306321><P Class=ENCC>
It takes a huge chunk of this volume..
<SYNC Start=310169><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=310406><P Class=ENCC>
just to prove that 1 + 1 = 2.
<SYNC Start=313884><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=316106><P Class=ENCC>
And a large part of that proof revolves around the problems of the finite and the infinite
<SYNC Start=321107><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=321129><P Class=ENCC>
and the paradoxes that Cantor's work had thrown up.
<SYNC Start=324603><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=327930><P Class=ENCC>
But despite the 'Principia',
<SYNC Start=329957><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=330020><P Class=ENCC>
there was now the feeling that the logic of math had undone itself
<SYNC Start=335173><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=335323><P Class=ENCC>
and it was Cantor's fault.
<SYNC Start=338639><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=340315><P Class=ENCC>
As the Austrian writer Musil wrote at the time,
<SYNC Start=344043><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=344255><P Class=ENCC>
suddenly mathematicians, those working in innermost region, discovered that
<SYNC Start=348892><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=349017><P Class=ENCC>
something in the foundations could absolutely not be put in order.
<SYNC Start=354127><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=354262><P Class=ENCC>
Indeed, they took a look at the bottom and found that the whole edifice was standing on air.
<SYNC Start=361253><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=367689><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor had stretched the limits of math and logic to breaking point, and paid for it.
<SYNC Start=373770><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=374174><P Class=ENCC>
Much of the last twenty years of his life were spent in and out of the asylum.
<SYNC Start=379392><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=382440><P Class=ENCC>
The last time that Cantor came here to the Nervenklinik in Halle was in 1917.
<SYNC Start=387669><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=387785><P Class=ENCC>
And he truly did not want to be here.
<SYNC Start=390467><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=390672><P Class=ENCC>
He wrote to his wife begging her to let him come home.
<SYNC Start=393611><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=393769><P Class=ENCC>
He was one of only two civilians left here.
<SYNC Start=396584><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=396609><P Class=ENCC>
The rest of the place was filled with the casualties of World War I.
<SYNC Start=400912><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=401697><P Class=ENCC>
But on the 6th January 1918, the greatest mathematician of his century died alone in his room,
<SYNC Start=409530><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=409757><P Class=ENCC>
his great project still unfinished.
<SYNC Start=412916><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=414429><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor had dislodged the pebble, which would one day start a landslide.
<SYNC Start=419867><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=420345><P Class=ENCC>
For him, it had all been held together, the paradoxes resolved, in God.
<SYNC Start=427026><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=429078><P Class=ENCC>
But what holds our ideas together, when God is dead?
<SYNC Start=433754><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=434240><P Class=ENCC>
Without God, the pebble is dislodged and the avalanche is unleashed.
<SYNC Start=439714><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=439972><P Class=ENCC>
And World War I had killed God.
<SYNC Start=443741><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=446656><P Class=ENCC>
Here at last was the slippage.
<SYNC Start=450103><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=453953><P Class=ENCC>
Hasn't there always been a desire in history of the West to find certainty
<SYNC Start=459526><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=459685><P Class=ENCC>
or maybe there wasn't so much desire at earlier eras
<SYNC Start=465300><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=465443><P Class=ENCC>
because the assumption was that we had that - there was God.
<SYNC Start=470628><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=470913><P Class=ENCC>
And even Descartes, despite all of his skepticism,
<SYNC Start=476378><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=476742><P Class=ENCC>
assumes for him unproblematically that there is God.
<SYNC Start=481865><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=482710><P Class=ENCC>
So what happens when that really comes into question
<SYNC Start=487590><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=487726><P Class=ENCC>
after 'the death of God' so to speak.
<SYNC Start=490864><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=491085><P Class=ENCC>
And along with the death of God is a loss of faith in some
<SYNC Start=497934><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=498090><P Class=ENCC>
supernatural order of which we are small part.
<SYNC Start=503843><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=506404><P Class=ENCC>
No one won the Great War.
<SYNC Start=508181><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=508520><P Class=ENCC>
Nothing was resolved at Versailles. It was merely an armistice.
<SYNC Start=512917><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=513399><P Class=ENCC>
And none of the intellectual crisis that preceded it had been resolved either.
<SYNC Start=518189><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=518577><P Class=ENCC>
Things like the 'Principia' had merely papered over the cracks.
<SYNC Start=522895><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=523292><P Class=ENCC>
In a way the 'Principia' was like the Versailles Treaty, only a lot more substantial.
<SYNC Start=527954><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=528108><P Class=ENCC>
This is basically 10000 tons of intellectual concrete poured over the cracks in mathematics.
<SYNC Start=533177><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=533683><P Class=ENCC>
And for a while it looked like it really might hold.
<SYNC Start=536027><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=536953><P Class=ENCC>
But then a young man came here to the University of Vienna to this library.
<SYNC Start=540665><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=540919><P Class=ENCC>
His name was Kurt Godel.
<SYNC Start=542699><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=543225><P Class=ENCC>
And the work that he did here
<SYNC Start=545737><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=545810><P Class=ENCC>
brought that dream of finding the perfect system of reasoning and logic crashing down.
<SYNC Start=551563><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=557879><P Class=ENCC>
Godel was born the year Boltzmann died - 1906.
<SYNC Start=561600><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=561867><P Class=ENCC>
He was an insatiably questioning boy, growing up in unstable times.
<SYNC Start=566783><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=566988><P Class=ENCC>
His family called him 'Mr. Why'.
<SYNC Start=570037><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=570403><P Class=ENCC>
But by the time he went to university, World War I was over.
<SYNC Start=574616><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=574748><P Class=ENCC>
But Austria like the rest of Europe was in the grip of the depression
<SYNC Start=578557><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=578722><P Class=ENCC>
and Hitler was forming the National Socialist Party.
<SYNC Start=581962><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=584107><P Class=ENCC>
Godel for his part became one of a brilliant group of young philosophers,
<SYNC Start=588740><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=588831><P Class=ENCC>
political thinkers, poets and scientists known as the 'Vienna Circle'.
<SYNC Start=593714><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=594098><P Class=ENCC>
Chaos was good, because it meant that there was no central authority
<SYNC Start=597190><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=597341><P Class=ENCC>
that was imposing ideas, so individuals could come up with their own ideas.
<SYNC Start=601478><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=601720><P Class=ENCC>
The chaos around them on the one hand had a liberating effect.
<SYNC Start=607455><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=607813><P Class=ENCC>
On the other hand, they were desperately searching for ideas that they could believe in
<SYNC Start=612649><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=612725><P Class=ENCC>
because everything else around them was crumbling in a heap.
<SYNC Start=615107><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=615270><P Class=ENCC>
So you want to find some beautiful ideas that you could believe in.
<SYNC Start=619680><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=619881><P Class=ENCC>
Though Godel was surrounded by radicals and revolutionary thinkers, he was not one himself.
<SYNC Start=626028><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=626180><P Class=ENCC>
He was an unworldly and exact man
<SYNC Start=629684><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=629738><P Class=ENCC>
who believed, like Hilbert, that math at least could be made whole again.
<SYNC Start=635707><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=636253><P Class=ENCC>
But it was not to be.
<SYNC Start=638599><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=639359><P Class=ENCC>
He certainly did not start out with trying to explode Hilbert's program also.
<SYNC Start=646174><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=646258><P Class=ENCC>
In fact, I think it came to Godel ultimately as a surprise
<SYNC Start=652213><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=652381><P Class=ENCC>
when he showed that its next step, to show the completeness of arithmetic, was unachievable.
<SYNC Start=659362><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=659641><P Class=ENCC>
There was actually something very mysterious happening in pure mathematics
<SYNC Start=662261><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=662432><P Class=ENCC>
in its own way as mysterious as black holes, as the big bang, as quantum uncertainty in the atom.
<SYNC Start=669009><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=669137><P Class=ENCC>
And this was Godel's incompleteness theorem. At that time, there was a mystery there.
<SYNC Start=672917><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=673051><P Class=ENCC>
The one place where you don't expect there to be mysteries is in pure reason..
<SYNC Start=676195><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=676357><P Class=ENCC>
this pure reason should be black and white, it should be really clear.
<SYNC Start=679275><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=679450><P Class=ENCC>
But pure reason, the clearest thing there is, was revealing that there were things that were unclear.
<SYNC Start=684890><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=696298><P Class=ENCC>
This is one of the cafes where the Vienna Circle used to meet regularly.
<SYNC Start=700291><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=700621><P Class=ENCC>
Late summer of 1930, Godel came to the cafe with two eminent colleagues.
<SYNC Start=705864><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=706470><P Class=ENCC>
Towards the end of the conversation, he just mentioned an idea he'd been working on,
<SYNC Start=710636><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=710752><P Class=ENCC>
which he called the 'incompleteness theorem'.
<SYNC Start=713201><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=713435><P Class=ENCC>
And what he told them, was that he had just proved
<SYNC Start=717834><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=717933><P Class=ENCC>
that all systems of mathematical logic were limited,
<SYNC Start=722470><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=722804><P Class=ENCC>
that there would always be some things, which while true,
<SYNC Start=726589><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=726653><P Class=ENCC>
would never be able to be proved to be true.
<SYNC Start=730185><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=730382><P Class=ENCC>
What Godel showed in his incompleteness theorem is that
<SYNC Start=735972><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=736491><P Class=ENCC>
no matter how large you make your basis of reasoning, your axioms, your set of axioms,
<SYNC Start=743104><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=743272><P Class=ENCC>
in arithmetic there would always be statements that are true but cannot be proved.
<SYNC Start=748612><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=752006><P Class=ENCC>
No matter how much data you have to build on,
<SYNC Start=756305><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=756475><P Class=ENCC>
you will never prove all true statements.
<SYNC Start=760806><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=763104><P Class=ENCC>
What this meant was that the great Renaissance dream,
<SYNC Start=767676><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=767931><P Class=ENCC>
that one day math and logic would be able to prove all things
<SYNC Start=771666><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=771728><P Class=ENCC>
and give us a God-like knowledge, that dream was over.
<SYNC Start=776129><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=776929><P Class=ENCC>
But this idea was so far away from what anyone else was working on,
<SYNC Start=781107><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=781167><P Class=ENCC>
what anyone else even suspected,
<SYNC Start=782671><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=782823><P Class=ENCC>
that neither of his colleagues understood what he had just told them.
<SYNC Start=787053><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=787316><P Class=ENCC>
It was as if there was an explosion but the blast wave hadn't hit them yet.
<SYNC Start=793366><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=797254><P Class=ENCC>
Unaware of what had happened in the Cafe, the very next day,
<SYNC Start=801160><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=801176><P Class=ENCC>
Hilbert, now the 'grand old man' of mathematics stood up and gave a lecture in Konigsberg
<SYNC Start=806654><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=806760><P Class=ENCC>
in which he said, "We must know. We will know."
<SYNC Start=812279><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=813794><P Class=ENCC>
The irony was that the very day before
<SYNC Start=817062><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=817148><P Class=ENCC>
Godel had proved that there were some things we would 'never' know.
<SYNC Start=822049><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=822886><P Class=ENCC>
Some didn't like it, some.. in particular for instance Hilbert.
<SYNC Start=827734><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=827898><P Class=ENCC>
It seemed that at the beginning he was quite annoyed and angry.
<SYNC Start=832192><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=832643><P Class=ENCC>
This is not a matter of liking it or not. It is..
<SYNC Start=835983><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=836146><P Class=ENCC>
you have here this proof and.. one has to live with it.
<SYNC Start=840482><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=841185><P Class=ENCC>
Are there any holes in Godel's argument?
<SYNC Start=842863><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=843001><P Class=ENCC>
No, there are not. This was a perfect argument. His argument was so crystal clear and obvious.
<SYNC Start=849065><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=850067><P Class=ENCC>
Godel had joined Hilbert in trying to solve the paradoxes uncovered by Cantor.
<SYNC Start=855639><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=855875><P Class=ENCC>
Instead, he had just proved that would never happen.
<SYNC Start=860058><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=860358><P Class=ENCC>
His work, springing directly from Cantor's work on infinity,
<SYNC Start=864643><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=864695><P Class=ENCC>
proved the paradoxes were unsolvable and there would be more of them.
<SYNC Start=870633><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=871905><P Class=ENCC>
But being right didn't make him popular.
<SYNC Start=875713><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=879676><P Class=ENCC>
So here we are again in the great courtyard of Vienna University
<SYNC Start=883041><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=883161><P Class=ENCC>
with the busts of all of the great thinkers
<SYNC Start=885747><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=885865><P Class=ENCC>
except for Kurt Godel. There's no bust to Godel here.
<SYNC Start=890160><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=890845><P Class=ENCC>
And I can't help but feel that at least part of the reason that he's not here
<SYNC Start=894720><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=894752><P Class=ENCC>
is simply due to the nature of his ideas.
<SYNC Start=897882><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=899625><P Class=ENCC>
Ah~ well you see nobody wants to face him.
<SYNC Start=901983><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=902059><P Class=ENCC>
In my opinion nobody wants to face the consequences of Godel.
<SYNC Start=905560><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=905951><P Class=ENCC>
You see, basically people want to go ahead with formal systems anyway
<SYNC Start=909209><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=909367><P Class=ENCC>
and as if Hilbert had it all right.
<SYNC Start=911647><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=912224><P Class=ENCC>
You see, and in my opinion Godel explodes that formalist view of mathematics,
<SYNC Start=918067><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=918132><P Class=ENCC>
that you can just mechanically grind away on a fixed set of concepts.
<SYNC Start=921959><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=921976><P Class=ENCC>
So even though, I believe Godel pulled out the rug and from under him(???) intellectually
<SYNC Start=926464><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=926480><P Class=ENCC>
nobody wants to face that fact.
<SYNC Start=927988><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=928144><P Class=ENCC>
So there's a very ambivalent attitude to Godel
<SYNC Start=930160><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=930164><P Class=ENCC>
even now a century after his birth.. very ambivalent attitude.
<SYNC Start=933973><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=934256><P Class=ENCC>
On the one hand, he is the greatest logician of all time so logicians acclaim him,
<SYNC Start=939142><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=939171><P Class=ENCC>
but on the other hand, they don't want people who are not logicians
<SYNC Start=942204><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=942240><P Class=ENCC>
to talk about the consequences of Godel's work
<SYNC Start=944275><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=944292><P Class=ENCC>
because the obvious conclusion from Godel's work is that logic is a failure,
<SYNC Start=947219><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=947353><P Class=ENCC>
.. let's move onto something else, and this would destroy the field.
<SYNC Start=950721><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=952739><P Class=ENCC>
Godel too felt the effects of his conclusion.
<SYNC Start=956068><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=956467><P Class=ENCC>
As he worked out the true extent of what he had done
<SYNC Start=959945><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=960147><P Class=ENCC>
incompleteness began to eat away at his own beliefs about the nature of mathematics.
<SYNC Start=965546><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=965871><P Class=ENCC>
His health began to deteriorate and he began to worry about the state of his mind.
<SYNC Start=971205><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=971866><P Class=ENCC>
In 1934 he had his first breakdown.
<SYNC Start=975432><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=976070><P Class=ENCC>
But it was after he recovered however that his real troubles began,
<SYNC Start=980662><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=980825><P Class=ENCC>
when he made a fateful decision.
<SYNC Start=983374><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=989736><P Class=ENCC>
Almost as soon as Godel has finished the incompleteness theorem,
<SYNC Start=992885><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=993016><P Class=ENCC>
he decides to work on the great unsolved problem of modern mathematics,
<SYNC Start=996727><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=996878><P Class=ENCC>
Cantor's continuum hypothesis.
<SYNC Start=999499><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=999896><P Class=ENCC>
And this is the effect that it has on him.
<SYNC Start=1001997><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1002603><P Class=ENCC>
These are some pages from one of Godel's workbooks. And they all look like this.
<SYNC Start=1008103><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1008974><P Class=ENCC>
Beautifully neat. Beautifully logical.
<SYNC Start=1012178><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1013592><P Class=ENCC>
Except for this one.
<SYNC Start=1014729><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1015128><P Class=ENCC>
This is the workbook where he is working on the continuum hypothesis.
<SYNC Start=1019031><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1023365><P Class=ENCC>
Godel, like Cantor before him, could neither solve the problem nor put it down
<SYNC Start=1029376><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1029649><P Class=ENCC>
even as it made him unwell.
<SYNC Start=1032104><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1046371><P Class=ENCC>
There could be a danger, and perhaps there is also a danger
<SYNC Start=1050001><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1050027><P Class=ENCC>
at the more ??? or personal, psychological level.
<SYNC Start=1053411><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1054448><P Class=ENCC>
If you're a person who is already prone to a kind of exaggerated
<SYNC Start=1061013><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1061137><P Class=ENCC>
intellectual self-reflection, self-consciousness,
<SYNC Start=1064562><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1068828><P Class=ENCC>
you may find that your intellectual work is, exaggerating, exacerbating that tendency
<SYNC Start=1075523><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1075584><P Class=ENCC>
which of course could make life more difficult to live.
<SYNC Start=1078857><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1084058><P Class=ENCC>
He calls this the worst year of his life.
<SYNC Start=1086906><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1087261><P Class=ENCC>
He has a massive nervous breakdown and ends up in a sanatorium
<SYNC Start=1091071><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1091158><P Class=ENCC>
just like Cantor.
<SYNC Start=1093113><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1094700><P Class=ENCC>
We're talking about people here who of course are
<SYNC Start=1098163><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1098194><P Class=ENCC>
capable of and maybe afflicted with the capacity to
<SYNC Start=1103258><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1103445><P Class=ENCC>
care very very much about things that are very very abstract,
<SYNC Start=1107260><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1107741><P Class=ENCC>
to lose themselves in their, in these intellectual problems.
<SYNC Start=1111930><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1117653><P Class=ENCC>
One of the sanatoria that Godel spent some time in is here,
<SYNC Start=1121543><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1121660><P Class=ENCC>
the Purkersdorf Sanatorium just outside of Vienna.
<SYNC Start=1124871><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1126824><P Class=ENCC>
The Purkersdorf itself was built to embody the philosophy
<SYNC Start=1130559><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1130673><P Class=ENCC>
that the calm smooth lines of rationalism are the cure for madness.
<SYNC Start=1135483><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1135823><P Class=ENCC>
Ironic then, that Godel driven mad by pushing the limits of rationalism
<SYNC Start=1140563><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1140710><P Class=ENCC>
should come here to recover.
<SYNC Start=1142493><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1146621><P Class=ENCC>
But while the man who'd proved there was a limit to rational certainty was in the sanatorium.
<SYNC Start=1152580><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1152750><P Class=ENCC>
outside a greater madness was unfolding.
<SYNC Start=1156574><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1156800><P Class=ENCC>
As a nation threw itself into the arms of a demagogue who promised there was certainty.
<SYNC Start=1162731><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1174697><P Class=ENCC>
Godel's madness passed. Austria's didn't.
<SYNC Start=1178700><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1178898><P Class=ENCC>
In 1939, Godel himself was attacked by a group of Nazi thugs.
<SYNC Start=1183789><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1184253><P Class=ENCC>
That same year he reluctantly left Austria for America.
<SYNC Start=1189002><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1204189><P Class=ENCC>
It was during these pre-war years that another brilliant young man
<SYNC Start=1208295><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1208428><P Class=ENCC>
Alan Turing enters our story.
<SYNC Start=1211476><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1215810><P Class=ENCC>
Turing is most famous for his wartime work at Bletchley Park
<SYNC Start=1219512><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1219573><P Class=ENCC>
breaking the German Enigma code.
<SYNC Start=1222821><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1231830><P Class=ENCC>
But he is also the man who made Godel's already devastating
<SYNC Start=1235848><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1235891><P Class=ENCC>
incompleteness theorem even worse.
<SYNC Start=1239168><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1241221><P Class=ENCC>
Turing was a much more practical man than Godel
<SYNC Start=1244401><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1246724><P Class=ENCC>
and simply wanted to make Godel's theorem clearer and simpler.
<SYNC Start=1251138><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1251683><P Class=ENCC>
How to do it came to him as he said later in a vision.
<SYNC Start=1255669><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1255922><P Class=ENCC>
That vision was the computer.
<SYNC Start=1258478><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1259503><P Class=ENCC>
The invention that has shaped the modern world was first imagined
<SYNC Start=1263858><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1264001><P Class=ENCC>
simply as the means to make Godel's incompleteness theorem more concrete
<SYNC Start=1269603><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1269775><P Class=ENCC>
because for many Godel's proof had simply been too abstract.
<SYNC Start=1275254><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1275935><P Class=ENCC>
It's an absolutely devastating result from a philosophical point of view.. we still haven't absorbed..
<SYNC Start=1280956><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1281072><P Class=ENCC>
but the proof was too superficial, it didn't get at the real heart of what was going on.
<SYNC Start=1286191><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1286432><P Class=ENCC>
It was more tantalizing than anything else.
<SYNC Start=1288189><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1288254><P Class=ENCC>
It was not a good reason for something so devastating and fundamental.
<SYNC Start=1292726><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1292754><P Class=ENCC>
It was too clever by half, it was too superficial, it said "I'm unprovable.", you know.. so what?
<SYNC Start=1298007><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1298122><P Class=ENCC>
This doesn't give you any insight into how serious the problem is.
<SYNC Start=1301855><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1301926><P Class=ENCC>
But Turing 5 years later his approach to incompleteness,
<SYNC Start=1307215><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1307362><P Class=ENCC>
that I felt was getting more in the right direction.
<SYNC Start=1311474><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1311876><P Class=ENCC>
Turing recast incompleteness in terms of computers
<SYNC Start=1315814><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1315954><P Class=ENCC>
and showed that since they are logic machines,
<SYNC Start=1319163><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1319339><P Class=ENCC>
incompleteness meant there would always be some problems they would never solve.
<SYNC Start=1324438><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1324598><P Class=ENCC>
A machine fed one of these problems would never stop.
<SYNC Start=1328740><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1328987><P Class=ENCC>
And worse, Turing proved there was no way of telling beforehand
<SYNC Start=1333662><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1333723><P Class=ENCC>
which these problems were.
<SYNC Start=1336836><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1340109><P Class=ENCC>
Godel had proved that in all systems of logic there would be some unsolvable problems
<SYNC Start=1345649><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1345744><P Class=ENCC>
.. which is bad enough.
<SYNC Start=1347553><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1347642><P Class=ENCC>
Then Turing comes along and makes matters much worse.
<SYNC Start=1351177><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1351414><P Class=ENCC>
At least with Godel, there was the hope that you could distinguish
<SYNC Start=1355056><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1355094><P Class=ENCC>
between the provable and the unprovable,
<SYNC Start=1357389><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1357541><P Class=ENCC>
and simply leave the unprovable to one side.
<SYNC Start=1360888><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1361174><P Class=ENCC>
What Turing does is prove that in fact there is no way of telling
<SYNC Start=1365060><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1365072><P Class=ENCC>
which will be the unprovable problems.
<SYNC Start=1368696><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1369023><P Class=ENCC>
So how do you know when to stop?
<SYNC Start=1372410><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1372638><P Class=ENCC>
You will never know whether the problem you're working on is simply extraordinarily difficult
<SYNC Start=1377329><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1377554><P Class=ENCC>
or if it's fundamentally unprovable.
<SYNC Start=1380109><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1380329><P Class=ENCC>
And that is Turing's 'halting problem'.
<SYNC Start=1383973><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1384319><P Class=ENCC>
But Turing makes it very down to earth because he talks about machines
<SYNC Start=1387801><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1387856><P Class=ENCC>
and he talks about whether a machine will halt or not.
<SYNC Start=1391262><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1391384><P Class=ENCC>
It's there in his paper.. he didn't call it, didn't speak of it in those terms
<SYNC Start=1395141><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1395190><P Class=ENCC>
but the ideas are really there in his original paper that's what I learnt.
<SYNC Start=1399043><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1399464><P Class=ENCC>
And this sounds so concrete and down to earth, you know computers are physical devices
<SYNC Start=1404641><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1404694><P Class=ENCC>
and you just start it running and there are two possibilities if you start a program running -
<SYNC Start=1410208><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1410364><P Class=ENCC>
a self contained program running with no input/output, it's just there. It's running on a computer.
<SYNC Start=1416109><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1416155><P Class=ENCC>
And one possibility is it's going to stop eventually saying
<SYNC Start=1418872><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1418932><P Class=ENCC>
it finishes the work, come up with an answer and stop, done, finished.
<SYNC Start=1422284><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1422396><P Class=ENCC>
The other possibility is it's going to be searching forever and never find what it's looking for,
<SYNC Start=1425414><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1425558><P Class=ENCC>
never finish the calculation, just go on forever. It's one or the other.
<SYNC Start=1428762><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1429101><P Class=ENCC>
The problem is: how can we tell that a program is never going to stop?
<SYNC Start=1432726><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1432844><P Class=ENCC>
And the answer is: there's no systematic general way to do it,
<SYNC Start=1435504><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1435552><P Class=ENCC>
and this is Turing's version of incompleteness.
<SYNC Start=1437819><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1437937><P Class=ENCC>
Turing gets incompleteness.. Godel's profound discovery..
<SYNC Start=1442095><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1442260><P Class=ENCC>
he gets it as a corollary of something more basic which is 'uncomputability',
<SYNC Start=1445837><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1445914><P Class=ENCC>
things which cannot be calculated, things which no computer can calculate.
<SYNC Start=1449652><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1449840><P Class=ENCC>
In certain domains, 'most' things cannot be calculated..
<SYNC Start=1452566><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1452718><P Class=ENCC>
But that's your work isn't it? You come along and make it worse again..
<SYNC Start=1455194><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1455367><P Class=ENCC>
- as if the news wasn't bad enough..<br>
- I do my best..
<SYNC Start=1457646><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1457824><P Class=ENCC>
Yes, I do my best. Some of it is already contained there in Turing's paper
<SYNC Start=1461558><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1461597><P Class=ENCC>
although he doesn't emphasize it.
<SYNC Start=1462701><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1464790><P Class=ENCC>
Startling as the halting problem was, the really profound part of incompleteness for Turing
<SYNC Start=1470980><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1471192><P Class=ENCC>
was not what it said about logic or computers, but what it said about us, and our minds.
<SYNC Start=1477865><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1478333><P Class=ENCC>
Were we or weren't we computers?
<SYNC Start=1481796><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1482294><P Class=ENCC>
It was the question that went to the heart of who Turing was.
<SYNC Start=1486569><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1487735><P Class=ENCC>
Turing was a man of two great loves.
<SYNC Start=1490203><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1490361><P Class=ENCC>
The first was for a young man, Christopher Morcom.
<SYNC Start=1494094><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1494668><P Class=ENCC>
The second was for the computer which he felt he had brought into this world.
<SYNC Start=1499425><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1501636><P Class=ENCC>
His love for Christopher had a unique place in his life.
<SYNC Start=1505191><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1505603><P Class=ENCC>
Because Christopher died tragically young.
<SYNC Start=1508378><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1508788><P Class=ENCC>
Turing never recaptured that first pure love
<SYNC Start=1511406><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1511734><P Class=ENCC>
but never let go of the memory of what it had been.
<SYNC Start=1515331><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1518705><P Class=ENCC>
But when Turing developed the idea of computer
<SYNC Start=1522107><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1522236><P Class=ENCC>
he began to fall in love in a very different way, with the sheer power of what he had imagined.
<SYNC Start=1528839><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1529210><P Class=ENCC>
He fell in love with the fantastic idea that one day computers would be more than machines,
<SYNC Start=1535594><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1535890><P Class=ENCC>
they would be like children capable of learning, thinking and communicating.
<SYNC Start=1541443><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1541759><P Class=ENCC>
And the scientist in him could also see that if our minds were like computers
<SYNC Start=1547302><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1547507><P Class=ENCC>
then here in our hands was the means to understand ourselves.
<SYNC Start=1553149><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1555797><P Class=ENCC>
What started with Cantor as a question from pure mathematics about the nature of infinity,
<SYNC Start=1561034><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1561524><P Class=ENCC>
in Godel's hands became a question about the limits of logic,
<SYNC Start=1564875><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1565274><P Class=ENCC>
and now with Turing it comes into focus as a question about us, and the nature of our minds.
<SYNC Start=1572662><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1573031><P Class=ENCC>
There is this sort of standard view - Turing was a computationalist
<SYNC Start=1576681><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1576684><P Class=ENCC>
and certainly in certain stage of his life he did take that point of view.
<SYNC Start=1580889><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1581042><P Class=ENCC>
Well maybe you can make one of these machines imitate the human mind.
<SYNC Start=1587037><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1587994><P Class=ENCC>
But he was of course well aware of these limitations of computers
<SYNC Start=1592281><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1592336><P Class=ENCC>
and that was one of his important results of his own.
<SYNC Start=1595297><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1595564><P Class=ENCC>
I think he may have shifted his view. He may have vacillated a bit
<SYNC Start=1599002><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1599254><P Class=ENCC>
and had one view and then another.
<SYNC Start=1601154><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1601182><P Class=ENCC>
But then when he really developed the computers as actual machines
<SYNC Start=1605227><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1605352><P Class=ENCC>
he sort of took off(???) and thought maybe these really are going to..
<SYNC Start=1608730><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1608790><P Class=ENCC>
it's a kind of.. when you get into a scientific thing you get totally..
<SYNC Start=1613207><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1613244><P Class=ENCC>
you think "maybe this is solving all problems".
<SYNC Start=1616412><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1616570><P Class=ENCC>
without realizing their limitations that are there, and which are part of his own theories.
<SYNC Start=1622057><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1623198><P Class=ENCC>
Turing understood that Godel's and his own work said that
<SYNC Start=1627279><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1627432><P Class=ENCC>
if our minds were computers then incompleteness would apply to us
<SYNC Start=1632558><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1632836><P Class=ENCC>
and the limitations of logic would be our limitations.
<SYNC Start=1636764><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1637029><P Class=ENCC>
We would not be capable of leaps of imagination beyond logic.
<SYNC Start=1641583><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1642060><P Class=ENCC>
Turing's personality is one thing. His mathematics doesn't have to be consistent with his personality.
<SYNC Start=1647351><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1647597><P Class=ENCC>
There is his work on artificial intelligence where I think he does believe that
<SYNC Start=1652222><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1652290><P Class=ENCC>
machines could become intelligent just like people or better or different but intelligent.
<SYNC Start=1659053><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1659254><P Class=ENCC>
But if you look at his first paper, when he points out that machines have limits
<SYNC Start=1664466><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1664628><P Class=ENCC>
because there are numbers.. in fact most numbers cannot be calculated by any machine.
<SYNC Start=1669425><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1669605><P Class=ENCC>
He's showing the power of the human mind
<SYNC Start=1671464><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1671486><P Class=ENCC>
to imagine things that escape what any machine could ever do.
<SYNC Start=1676593><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1676775><P Class=ENCC>
That may go against his own philosophy, he may think of himself as a machine..
<SYNC Start=1680673><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1680778><P Class=ENCC>
but his very first paper is smashing machines..
<SYNC Start=1685404><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1685431><P Class=ENCC>
it's creating machines.. and then it's pointing out their devastating limitations.
<SYNC Start=1689521><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1690824><P Class=ENCC>
Turing was well aware of these problems
<SYNC Start=1693254><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1693338><P Class=ENCC>
but desperately wanted to prove he could get the fullness of the human mind from mere computation.
<SYNC Start=1700224><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1700510><P Class=ENCC>
And it wasn't just the scientist in him that wanted to do this.
<SYNC Start=1704733><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1705306><P Class=ENCC>
Turing's personal philosophy which he stuck to all his life
<SYNC Start=1709278><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1709323><P Class=ENCC>
was to be free from hypocrisy, compromise and deceit.
<SYNC Start=1713060><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1713369><P Class=ENCC>
Turing was a homosexual when it was both illegal and even dangerous.
<SYNC Start=1717696><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1717762><P Class=ENCC>
Yet he never hid it, nor made it an issue.
<SYNC Start=1721239><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1725355><P Class=ENCC>
With computers there are no lies or hypocrisy.
<SYNC Start=1729278><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1729545><P Class=ENCC>
If we were computers then we were the kind of creature Turing wanted us to be.
<SYNC Start=1736087><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1738157><P Class=ENCC>
People could vacillate. They could have one view and then wonder about this,
<SYNC Start=1741305><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1741310><P Class=ENCC>
"Is this really right?" and then have another view and play around,
<SYNC Start=1744199><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1744207><P Class=ENCC>
If they're good scientists, they will do that. They won't just doggedly follow one point of view.
<SYNC Start=1749882><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1749945><P Class=ENCC>
So I suspect Turing vacillated rather.
<SYNC Start=1753051><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1753122><P Class=ENCC>
But I think in a lot of his analyses and criticisms of
<SYNC Start=1757970><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1757979><P Class=ENCC>
other people who criticized his view
<SYNC Start=1761891><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1762038><P Class=ENCC>
he would show the flaws in their arguments and say,
<SYNC Start=1764716><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1764905><P Class=ENCC>
"Well look, it may still be, despite all these theorems we know about non-computability, .."
<SYNC Start=1769550><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1769619><P Class=ENCC>
"..it still might be that we are computational entities."
<SYNC Start=1772849><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1772871><P Class=ENCC>
and then point out "well, because of this and this loophole" and so on.
<SYNC Start=1776017><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1776139><P Class=ENCC>
And maybe he came to believe those loopholes were sufficient to get him out.
<SYNC Start=1780330><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1780537><P Class=ENCC>
But yet he did do these things like looking at oracle machines which were sort of super Turing machines
<SYNC Start=1786456><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1786545><P Class=ENCC>
and beyond them they're not machines that you could see anywhere constructing out of ordinary stuff.
<SYNC Start=1790877><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1791287><P Class=ENCC>
But nevertheless as a theoretical entity
<SYNC Start=1793464><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1793682><P Class=ENCC>
these devices were theoretical things that would go beyond standard computers.
<SYNC Start=1799548><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1803186><P Class=ENCC>
This tension between the human and the computational was central to Turing's life.
<SYNC Start=1808967><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1809296><P Class=ENCC>
And he lived with it until the events which led to his death.
<SYNC Start=1813841><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1817156><P Class=ENCC>
After the war, Turing increasingly found himself drawing the attention of the Security Services.
<SYNC Start=1823362><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1823886><P Class=ENCC>
In the Cold War, homosexuality was seen as not only illegal and immoral
<SYNC Start=1829500><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1829552><P Class=ENCC>
but also a security risk.
<SYNC Start=1832897><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1835752><P Class=ENCC>
So when in March 1952 he was arrested, charged and found guilty of engaging in a homosexual act
<SYNC Start=1843924><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1844106><P Class=ENCC>
the authorities decided he was a problem that needed to be fixed.
<SYNC Start=1849322><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1849974><P Class=ENCC>
They would chemically castrate him by injecting him with the female hormone, estrogen.
<SYNC Start=1856287><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1857336><P Class=ENCC>
Turing was being treated as no more than a machine,
<SYNC Start=1860356><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1860575><P Class=ENCC>
chemically reprogrammed to eliminate the uncertainty of his sexuality
<SYNC Start=1865890><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1865894><P Class=ENCC>
and the risk they felt it posed to security and order.
<SYNC Start=1870203><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1871395><P Class=ENCC>
To his horror he found the treatment affected his mind and his body.
<SYNC Start=1876179><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1876498><P Class=ENCC>
He grew breasts, his moods altered and he worried about his mind.
<SYNC Start=1881827><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1882561><P Class=ENCC>
For a man who'd always been authentic and at one with himself
<SYNC Start=1886426><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1886466><P Class=ENCC>
it was as if he had been injected with hypocrisy.
<SYNC Start=1890598><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1894264><P Class=ENCC>
On the 7th June 1954, Turing was found dead.
<SYNC Start=1898610><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1898970><P Class=ENCC>
At his bedside an apple from which he had taken several bites.
<SYNC Start=1903667><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1903976><P Class=ENCC>
Turing had poisoned the apple with cyanide.
<SYNC Start=1907334><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1914026><P Class=ENCC>
Turing was dead, but his question was not.
<SYNC Start=1917995><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1918345><P Class=ENCC>
Whether the mind was a computer and so limited by logic, or somehow able to transcend logic
<SYNC Start=1924792><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1925087><P Class=ENCC>
was now the question that came to trouble the mind of Kurt Godel.
<SYNC Start=1929529><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1932307><P Class=ENCC>
Godel was now working in America at the Institute for Advanced Study
<SYNC Start=1936644><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1936727><P Class=ENCC>
where he continued to work as obsessively as he ever had.
<SYNC Start=1940466><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1947579><P Class=ENCC>
Of course, Godel recovered from his time in the sanatorium.
<SYNC Start=1950514><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1950681><P Class=ENCC>
But by the time he got here to the Institute for Advanced Study in America
<SYNC Start=1954106><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1954139><P Class=ENCC>
he was a very peculiar man.
<SYNC Start=1956446><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1961522><P Class=ENCC>
One of the stories they tell about him is
<SYNC Start=1963325><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1963440><P Class=ENCC>
if he was caught in the commons with a crowd of other people, he so hated physical contact
<SYNC Start=1968536><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1968683><P Class=ENCC>
that he would stand very still so as to plot the perfect course out
<SYNC Start=1972719><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1972827><P Class=ENCC>
so as not to have to actually touch anyone.
<SYNC Start=1975289><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1975476><P Class=ENCC>
He also felt he was being poisoned by what he called 'bad air'
<SYNC Start=1978760><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1978830><P Class=ENCC>
from heating systems and air conditioners
<SYNC Start=1980887><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1981052><P Class=ENCC>
and most of all he thought his food was being poisoned.
<SYNC Start=1983563><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1983840><P Class=ENCC>
He insisted his wife taste all his food for him.
<SYNC Start=1987385><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1987536><P Class=ENCC>
He would sometimes order oranges and then send them straight back claiming they were poisoned.
<SYNC Start=1992510><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1996538><P Class=ENCC>
Peculiar as Godel was, his genius was undimmed.
<SYNC Start=2001134><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2001348><P Class=ENCC>
Unlike Turing, Godel could not believe we were like computers.
<SYNC Start=2006078><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2006381><P Class=ENCC>
He wanted to show how the mind had a way of reaching truth outside logic
<SYNC Start=2011168><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2011413><P Class=ENCC>
and what it would mean if it couldn't.
<SYNC Start=2014276><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2015302><P Class=ENCC>
In principle you could have a machine grinding away deducing all the consequences
<SYNC Start=2018693><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2018715><P Class=ENCC>
of a fixed set of principles.
<SYNC Start=2021358><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2021401><P Class=ENCC>
And mathematics would be static and dead.
<SYNC Start=2023199><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2023203><P Class=ENCC>
It would just be a question of mechanically deducing all the consequences.
<SYNC Start=2027238><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2027284><P Class=ENCC>
And so mathematicians in a sense would just be machines.
<SYNC Start=2032017><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2032250><P Class=ENCC>
I mean Turing did think that he was a machine. I think he did.
<SYNC Start=2035649><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2035762><P Class=ENCC>
And I think that paper on the imitation game shows that.
<SYNC Start=2041472><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2041672><P Class=ENCC>
And Godel clearly did not think that he was a machine.
<SYNC Start=2044192><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2044226><P Class=ENCC>
He thought that he was divine and that human beings have a divine spark in them
<SYNC Start=2048217><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2048254><P Class=ENCC>
that enables them to create new mathematics I think.
<SYNC Start=2051029><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2052621><P Class=ENCC>
Why was Godel so convinced humans had this spark of creativity?
<SYNC Start=2057525><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2058023><P Class=ENCC>
The key to his belief comes from a deep conviction he shared
<SYNC Start=2061562><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2061574><P Class=ENCC>
with one of the few close friends he ever had.
<SYNC Start=2064899><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2065220><P Class=ENCC>
That other Austrian genius who had settled at the Institute,
<SYNC Start=2069883><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2069959><P Class=ENCC>
Albert Einstein.
<SYNC Start=2071942><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2073916><P Class=ENCC>
Einstein used to say that he came here to the Institute for Advanced Studies
<SYNC Start=2077739><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2077787><P Class=ENCC>
simply for the privilege of walking home with Kurt Godel.
<SYNC Start=2080703><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2081001><P Class=ENCC>
And what was it that held this most unlikely of couples together?
<SYNC Start=2083847><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2084078><P Class=ENCC>
On the one had you've got the warm and avuncular Einstein
<SYNC Start=2086687><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2086734><P Class=ENCC>
and on the other the rather cold, wizened and withdrawn Kurt Godel.
<SYNC Start=2090968><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2091221><P Class=ENCC>
And the answer comes I think from something else that Einstein said.
<SYNC Start=2094120><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2094304><P Class=ENCC>
He said that God may be subtle but he's not malicious.
<SYNC Start=2098552><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2098789><P Class=ENCC>
What does that mean? Well, it means for Einstein is that
<SYNC Start=2101337><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2101380><P Class=ENCC>
however complicated the universe might be, there will always be beautiful rules by which it works.
<SYNC Start=2107602><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2108070><P Class=ENCC>
Godel believed the same idea from his point of view to mean that
<SYNC Start=2111914><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2112112><P Class=ENCC>
God would never have put us into a creation that we could then not understand.
<SYNC Start=2116843><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2117359><P Class=ENCC>
The question is, how is it that Kurt Godel can believe that God isn't malicious, that it's all understandable?
<SYNC Start=2122992><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2123145><P Class=ENCC>
Because Godel is the man who's proved that some things cannot be proven logically and rationally.
<SYNC Start=2130055><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2130743><P Class=ENCC>
So surely God must be malicious?
<SYNC Start=2133499><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2134066><P Class=ENCC>
The way he gets out of it is Godel, like Einstein, believed deeply in intuition
<SYNC Start=2139158><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2139293><P Class=ENCC>
that we can know things outside of logic because we just intuit them.
<SYNC Start=2144791><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2145113><P Class=ENCC>
And they believed it because they have both felt it. They've both had their moments of intuition.
<SYNC Start=2149968><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2150260><P Class=ENCC>
Just like Cantor had had his.
<SYNC Start=2151772><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2152016><P Class=ENCC>
He talks about new principles that the mathematician,
<SYNC Start=2157383><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2157448><P Class=ENCC>
closing your eyes, tuning out the real world,
<SYNC Start=2160406><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2160524><P Class=ENCC>
you can try to perceive directly by your mathematical intuition the Platonic world of ideas
<SYNC Start=2165552><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2165621><P Class=ENCC>
and come up with new principles which you can then use
<SYNC Start=2168188><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2168232><P Class=ENCC>
to extend the current set of principles in mathematics.
<SYNC Start=2171679><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2171902><P Class=ENCC>
And he viewed this as a way of getting around the limitations of his own theorem.
<SYNC Start=2175393><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2175468><P Class=ENCC>
I don't think he thought there was any limit to the mathematics that human beings were capable of.
<SYNC Start=2179898><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2180188><P Class=ENCC>
But how do you prove this?
<SYNC Start=2181714><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2181822><P Class=ENCC>
There's a interpretation that Godel himself drew. It was that computers are limited.
<SYNC Start=2190847><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2191339><P Class=ENCC>
He certainly tried again and again to work out that
<SYNC Start=2196239><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2196257><P Class=ENCC>
the human mind transcends the computer
<SYNC Start=2199526><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2199796><P Class=ENCC>
in the sense that he can understand things to be true
<SYNC Start=2204591><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2204633><P Class=ENCC>
that cannot be proved by a computer program.
<SYNC Start=2207498><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2207780><P Class=ENCC>
Godel also was wrestling with finding means of knowledge
<SYNC Start=2213452><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2213559><P Class=ENCC>
which are not based on experience and on mathematical reasoning
<SYNC Start=2217790><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2217804><P Class=ENCC>
but on some sort of intuition.
<SYNC Start=2219909><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2220253><P Class=ENCC>
The frustration for Godel was getting anyone to understand him.
<SYNC Start=2224085><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2224457><P Class=ENCC>
I think people very often, for some reason, misunderstand Godel, certainly his intention.
<SYNC Start=2230247><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2230711><P Class=ENCC>
Godel was deliberately trying to show that
<SYNC Start=2233828><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2233931><P Class=ENCC>
what one might call mathematical intuition, I here refer to what he called mathematical intuition
<SYNC Start=2238804><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2238854><P Class=ENCC>
and he was demonstrating, clearly in my mind, demonstrated
<SYNC Start=2243394><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2243473><P Class=ENCC>
that this is outside just following formal rules.
<SYNC Start=2246523><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2247112><P Class=ENCC>
And I don't know, some people picked up on what he did and said,
<SYNC Start=2250996><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2251196><P Class=ENCC>
"Well he's shown there are unprovable results and therefore beyond the mind."
<SYNC Start=2254142><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2254478><P Class=ENCC>
What he really showed was that for any system that you adopt,
<SYNC Start=2259309><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2259425><P Class=ENCC>
which in a sense the mind has been removed from it
<SYNC Start=2262087><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2262122><P Class=ENCC>
because your mind is used to lay down the system,
<SYNC Start=2265402><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2265521><P Class=ENCC>
but from there on it takes over and you ask what's it's scope.
<SYNC Start=2269558><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2269776><P Class=ENCC>
And what Godel showed is that it's scope is always limited and that the mind can go beyond it.
<SYNC Start=2274522><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2274816><P Class=ENCC>
Here's the man who has said certain things cannot be proved within any rational and logical system.
<SYNC Start=2281609><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2281830><P Class=ENCC>
But he says that doesn't matter because the human mind isn't limited that way. We have Intuition.
<SYNC Start=2286774><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2287525><P Class=ENCC>
But then of course, the one thing he really must prove to other people is the existence of intuition.
<SYNC Start=2293761><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2294086><P Class=ENCC>
The one thing you'll never be able to prove.
<SYNC Start=2296733><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2297058><P Class=ENCC>
He has these drafts of papers where he expresses himself very strongly
<SYNC Start=2301982><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2302057><P Class=ENCC>
but he wasn't satisfied with that,
<SYNC Start=2304716><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2304789><P Class=ENCC>
because he couldn't prove a theorem about creativity or intuition.
<SYNC Start=2307364><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2307401><P Class=ENCC>
It was just a gut feeling that he had.. and he wasn't satisfied with that.
<SYNC Start=2312046><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2313066><P Class=ENCC>
And so Godel, like Cantor before him,
<SYNC Start=2316081><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2316145><P Class=ENCC>
had finally found a problem he desperately wanted to solve but could not.
<SYNC Start=2321623><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2322102><P Class=ENCC>
He was now caught in a loop, a logical paradox from which his mind could not escape.
<SYNC Start=2328224><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2328972><P Class=ENCC>
And at the same time he slowly starved himself to death.
<SYNC Start=2333154><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2338291><P Class=ENCC>
Using mathematics to show the limits of mathematics is psychologically very contradictory.
<SYNC Start=2346011><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2348008><P Class=ENCC>
It's clear in Godel's case that he appreciated this.
<SYNC Start=2352566><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2353689><P Class=ENCC>
His own life has this paradox.
<SYNC Start=2355959><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2356066><P Class=ENCC>
What Godel is, is the mind thinking about itself and what it can achieve at the deepest level.
<SYNC Start=2361465><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2372771><P Class=ENCC>
Someone used the phrase 'the vertigo of the modern'.
<SYNC Start=2375572><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2375599><P Class=ENCC>
You can be led into that particular reflexive whirlpool
<SYNC Start=2379539><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2379600><P Class=ENCC>
where you begin to think about thinking about thinking about thinking..
<SYNC Start=2382989><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2383140><P Class=ENCC>
and you find yourself entangled in your own thoughts.
<SYNC Start=2387769><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2389852><P Class=ENCC>
Well, that seems to me almost the quintessence of the modern moment.
<SYNC Start=2393830><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2393984><P Class=ENCC>
because there you have.. what you could call a 'paradox of self-reflection'.
<SYNC Start=2398739><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2399136><P Class=ENCC>
The kind of madness that you find associated with modernism is a kind of madness
<SYNC Start=2404583><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2404607><P Class=ENCC>
that's' bound up with not only rationality but with all the paradoxes that arise
<SYNC Start=2410665><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2410684><P Class=ENCC>
from self-consciousness, from the consciousness contemplating it's own being as consciousness,
<SYNC Start=2415808><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2415934><P Class=ENCC>
or from logic contemplating it's own being as logic.
<SYNC Start=2419246><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2421579><P Class=ENCC>
Even though he's shown that logic has certain limitations
<SYNC Start=2425077><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2425124><P Class=ENCC>
he's still so drawn to that to the significance of the rational and logical
<SYNC Start=2430917><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2431133><P Class=ENCC>
that he desperately wants to prove whatever is most important logically
<SYNC Start=2435081><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2435154><P Class=ENCC>
even if it's an alternative to logic.
<SYNC Start=2437553><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2438238><P Class=ENCC>
How strange.. and what a testimony to his inability to separate himself
<SYNC Start=2444481><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2444664><P Class=ENCC>
to detach himself from the need for logical proof. Godel of all people.
<SYNC Start=2449795><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2458311><P Class=ENCC>
At the beginning of our story, Cantor had hoped that at its deepest level
<SYNC Start=2463854><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2464056><P Class=ENCC>
mathematics would rest on certainties which for him were the mind of God.
<SYNC Start=2469911><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2470250><P Class=ENCC>
But instead, he had uncovered uncertainties
<SYNC Start=2473890><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2475195><P Class=ENCC>
which Turing and Godel then proved would never go away.
<SYNC Start=2479117><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2479320><P Class=ENCC>
They were an inescapable part of the very foundations of math and logic.
<SYNC Start=2484785><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2490891><P Class=ENCC>
The almost religious belief that there was a perfect logic
<SYNC Start=2495748><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2495830><P Class=ENCC>
which governed a world of certainties had unravelled itself.
<SYNC Start=2500475><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2501053><P Class=ENCC>
Logic had revealed the limitations of logic.
<SYNC Start=2504609><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2504827><P Class=ENCC>
The search for certainty had revealed uncertainty.
<SYNC Start=2509027><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2510319><P Class=ENCC>
There's a fashionable solution to the problem
<SYNC Start=2513097><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2513146><P Class=ENCC>
which is basically in my opinion people might hate me for this
<SYNC Start=2516610><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2516784><P Class=ENCC>
is sweeping it under the carpet. But you see the problem is
<SYNC Start=2519718><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2519744><P Class=ENCC>
I don't think you want to solve the problem.
<SYNC Start=2521552><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2521703><P Class=ENCC>
I think it's much more fun to live with the problem.
<SYNC Start=2524386><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2524683><P Class=ENCC>
It's much more creative.
<SYNC Start=2526408><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2528404><P Class=ENCC>
This notion of absolute certainty.. there is no absolute certainty in human life.
<SYNC Start=2534157><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2534380><P Class=ENCC>
But our knowledge.. our possible knowledge of this world of ideas
<SYNC Start=2538985><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2539089><P Class=ENCC>
can only be incomplete and finite because we're incomplete and finite.
<SYNC Start=2543335><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2544084><P Class=ENCC>
The problem is that today some knowledge still feels too dangerous.
<SYNC Start=2549825><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2550201><P Class=ENCC>
Because our times are not so different to Cantor or Boltzmann or Godel's time.
<SYNC Start=2555952><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2565583><P Class=ENCC>
We too feel things we thought were solid being challenged,
<SYNC Start=2570366><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2570471><P Class=ENCC>
feel our certainties slipping away.
<SYNC Start=2573552><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2573933><P Class=ENCC>
And so, as then, we still desperately want to cling to a belief in certainty.
<SYNC Start=2580171><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2580491><P Class=ENCC>
It makes us feel safe.
<SYNC Start=2582378><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2585264><P Class=ENCC>
At the end of this journey, the question I think we are left with
<SYNC Start=2589411><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2589492><P Class=ENCC>
is actually the same as it was in Cantor and Boltzmann's time.
<SYNC Start=2593225><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2593514><P Class=ENCC>
Are we grown up enough to live with uncertainties?
<SYNC Start=2597341><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2597546><P Class=ENCC>
Or will we repeat the mistakes of the 20th century
<SYNC Start=2601060><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2601261><P Class=ENCC>
and pledge blind allegiance to yet another certainty?
<SYNC Start=2606341><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
</BODY>
